1
00:00:09,218 --> 00:00:11,220
[SOFT PIANO MUSIC PLAYING]

2
00:00:51,969 --> 00:00:54,095
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

3
00:00:54,096 --> 00:00:56,891
MAN: [SINGING] <i>I telegraphed and phoned</i>

4
00:00:57,683 --> 00:01:02,480
<i>I sent air mail special, too</i>

5
00:01:03,063 --> 00:01:04,063
Yeah, I know.

6
00:01:04,064 --> 00:01:10,946
[SINGING] <i>Answer was goodbye
There was even postage due</i>

7
00:01:13,491 --> 00:01:14,699
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

8
00:01:14,700 --> 00:01:18,245
<i>I fell in love just once</i>

9
00:01:18,913 --> 00:01:21,624
<i>And then it had to be with you</i>

10
00:01:22,374 --> 00:01:23,709
Triple rhyme.

11
00:01:26,212 --> 00:01:31,926
[SINGING] <i>Everything happens to me</i>

12
00:01:36,931 --> 00:01:38,349
Oh, fuck.

13
00:01:39,642 --> 00:01:40,684
[GROANS]

14
00:01:42,061 --> 00:01:43,186
Yeah.

15
00:01:43,187 --> 00:01:44,979
ANNOUNCER: [ON RADIO]
<i>WQXR notes the passing</i>

16
00:01:44,980 --> 00:01:47,649
<i>of one of America's foremost songwriters,</i>

17
00:01:47,650 --> 00:01:52,028
<i>Lorenz Hart, who died last night
at Doctors Hospital in Manhattan</i>

18
00:01:52,029 --> 00:01:54,155
<i>from complications of pneumonia.</i>

19
00:01:54,156 --> 00:01:56,991
<i>Mr. Hart was 48 years old.</i>

20
00:01:56,992 --> 00:02:00,829
<i>For over 20 years,
Hart and his partner, Richard Rodgers,</i>

21
00:02:00,830 --> 00:02:03,581
<i>Rodgers wrote the music, Hart the words,</i>

22
00:02:03,582 --> 00:02:08,795
<i>combined their respective geniuses
to create a string of musical-comedy hits.</i>

23
00:02:08,796 --> 00:02:12,090
<i>Often referred to as America's
Gilbert and Sullivan,</i>

24
00:02:12,091 --> 00:02:15,385
<i>Rodgers and Hart will be remembered
for such songs as,</i>

25
00:02:15,386 --> 00:02:18,346
My Funny Valentine,
The Lady Is A Tramp,

26
00:02:18,347 --> 00:02:22,684
Where or When, With A Song In My Heart,
Isn't It Romantic?,

27
00:02:22,685 --> 00:02:25,186
My Heart Stood Still, Bewitched,

28
00:02:25,187 --> 00:02:28,273
I Didn't Know What Time It Was,
Manhattan,

29
00:02:28,274 --> 00:02:29,692
<i>and</i> Blue Moon.

30
00:02:30,526 --> 00:02:32,528
[CHOIR VOCALIZING]

31
00:02:33,737 --> 00:02:36,155
[SINGING]
<i>Okla-Okla-Okla-Okla-Okla</i>

32
00:02:36,156 --> 00:02:38,534
<i>Okla-Okla-Okla-Okla-Okla</i>

33
00:02:38,659 --> 00:02:41,703
<i>We know we belong to the land</i>

34
00:02:41,704 --> 00:02:42,954
Here comes "grand."

35
00:02:42,955 --> 00:02:46,792
<i>And the land we belong to is grand
And when we say</i>

36
00:02:47,293 --> 00:02:51,045
<i>Yow! Ayipioeeay!</i>

37
00:02:51,046 --> 00:02:54,591
<i>We're only sayin'
"You're doin' fine, Oklahoma!"</i>

38
00:02:54,592 --> 00:02:56,634
I need a drink.

39
00:02:56,635 --> 00:02:58,888
- Lorry.
- I'll see you later, Mom.

40
00:02:59,013 --> 00:03:00,138
<i>L-A-H-O-M-A</i>

41
00:03:00,139 --> 00:03:01,222
[EXHALES]

42
00:03:01,223 --> 00:03:06,311
<i>Oklahoma!</i>

43
00:03:06,312 --> 00:03:07,437
<i>Yow!</i>

44
00:03:07,438 --> 00:03:08,981
[AUDIENCE CHEERING]

45
00:03:17,364 --> 00:03:19,366
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION]

46
00:03:26,790 --> 00:03:27,791
[PLAYING MELLOW TUNE]

47
00:03:28,792 --> 00:03:29,919
[DOOR OPENS]

48
00:03:50,648 --> 00:03:55,193
All right. For the last time,
put the letters on the table.

49
00:03:55,194 --> 00:03:58,279
"If Laszlo and the cause
mean that much to you,

50
00:03:58,280 --> 00:04:00,074
"you won't stop at anything."

51
00:04:00,950 --> 00:04:03,911
All right, I'll make it easy on you.

52
00:04:04,703 --> 00:04:07,956
"Go ahead, shoot.
You'd be doing me a favor."

53
00:04:07,957 --> 00:04:10,708
Just remember,
I got this gun pointed at your dick.

54
00:04:10,709 --> 00:04:13,211
Oh. That's my least vulnerable spot.

55
00:04:13,212 --> 00:04:15,004
[BOTH LAUGHING]

56
00:04:15,005 --> 00:04:17,590
BARTENDER: Jesus Christ! How many times
have we seen that picture?

57
00:04:17,591 --> 00:04:19,884
Worst line in <i>Casablanca?</i>

58
00:04:19,885 --> 00:04:23,097
"Well, a precedent is being broken."

59
00:04:23,847 --> 00:04:28,476
"A precedent is being broken"?
How can you break a goddamn precedent?

60
00:04:28,477 --> 00:04:31,855
Do they even speak English over there
in Hollywood?

61
00:04:32,439 --> 00:04:35,024
Still, you have to love Claude Rains.

62
00:04:35,025 --> 00:04:37,694
He makes that picture.

63
00:04:37,695 --> 00:04:39,570
- Sure.
- HART: You know why he's so great?

64
00:04:39,571 --> 00:04:42,365
He's a leading man, and he's short,

65
00:04:42,366 --> 00:04:44,951
which proves you can be both.

66
00:04:44,952 --> 00:04:46,244
And I love this.

67
00:04:46,245 --> 00:04:47,912
He says to Ilsa,

68
00:04:47,913 --> 00:04:52,917
<i>"Mademoiselle,</i> he's the kind of man that,
if I were a woman

69
00:04:52,918 --> 00:04:55,962
"and I were not around,
I should be in love with Rick."

70
00:04:55,963 --> 00:04:56,921
[CHUCKLES]

71
00:04:56,922 --> 00:05:00,341
Think about it. Whom does he end up with
at the end of the picture?

72
00:05:00,342 --> 00:05:04,303
Who's strolling away together arm in arm
into the fog?

73
00:05:04,304 --> 00:05:05,930
You're saying Rick and Captain Renault...

74
00:05:05,931 --> 00:05:07,306
What do you think goes on over there

75
00:05:07,307 --> 00:05:09,726
at the Free French garrison
in Brazzaville?

76
00:05:09,727 --> 00:05:12,021
That is a scene they can't show you.

77
00:05:12,521 --> 00:05:15,065
Okay. Best line in <i>Casablanca?</i>

78
00:05:17,526 --> 00:05:19,777
HART AND BARTENDER: "Nobody ever
loved me that much."

79
00:05:19,778 --> 00:05:21,487
Isn't that magnificent?

80
00:05:21,488 --> 00:05:24,782
Six words.
"Nobody ever loved me that much."

81
00:05:24,783 --> 00:05:26,909
[SCOFFS] And, really,
who's ever been loved enough?

82
00:05:26,910 --> 00:05:28,453
Who's ever been loved half enough?

83
00:05:28,454 --> 00:05:29,621
Would you get me a shot?

84
00:05:30,914 --> 00:05:32,040
Larry, you told me
under no circumstances...

85
00:05:32,041 --> 00:05:33,082
I'm just going to look at it.

86
00:05:33,083 --> 00:05:34,375
- [INHALES DEEPLY]
- Take the measure

87
00:05:34,376 --> 00:05:36,669
of its amber heft in my hand.

88
00:05:36,670 --> 00:05:39,297
- You told me not...
- Just give me the drink.

89
00:05:39,298 --> 00:05:40,883
[EXHALES DEEPLY]

90
00:05:44,720 --> 00:05:46,471
Did I tell you what Elizabeth told me?

91
00:05:46,472 --> 00:05:48,347
That's the girl I'm meeting here tonight.

92
00:05:48,348 --> 00:05:50,266
- You mean the one you...
- Eddie, Eddie, Eddie.

93
00:05:50,267 --> 00:05:53,603
- What?
- Show some class, all right?

94
00:05:53,604 --> 00:05:56,022
Her mother is going to come
walking in here any second.

95
00:05:56,023 --> 00:05:57,690
- Sorry.
- Seriously.

96
00:05:57,691 --> 00:06:02,361
I... I adore this girl.
And, I'm telling you, this is beyond sex.

97
00:06:02,362 --> 00:06:04,614
- What's beyond sex?
- I don't understand it.

98
00:06:04,615 --> 00:06:08,826
She's completely undeserving,
but isn't that the way it always is?

99
00:06:08,827 --> 00:06:11,704
"Irrational adoration."
That's the phrase she came up with.

100
00:06:11,705 --> 00:06:13,623
She's a poet, too. Did I tell you that?

101
00:06:13,624 --> 00:06:16,209
Oh, and would you give me
a shot of club soda?

102
00:06:16,210 --> 00:06:20,089
I'll drink one and admire the other.

103
00:06:20,672 --> 00:06:22,424
So, this girl...

104
00:06:24,259 --> 00:06:26,678
You really, you know,

105
00:06:27,596 --> 00:06:29,847
with a 20-year-old college girl, huh?

106
00:06:29,848 --> 00:06:32,809
It is more complicated
than you could possibly imagine.

107
00:06:32,810 --> 00:06:34,353
Uh, leave the bottle.

108
00:06:34,895 --> 00:06:36,813
It's a visual poem.

109
00:06:36,814 --> 00:06:38,439
You're not giving me any details here.

110
00:06:38,440 --> 00:06:40,817
You know what my secret goal is
for the rest of this year?

111
00:06:40,818 --> 00:06:42,527
- What?
- I'm serious. Really.

112
00:06:42,528 --> 00:06:45,823
My secret goal is to stop being so scared.

113
00:06:46,907 --> 00:06:49,742
- Elizabeth Weiland. For...
- HART: Those are mine!

114
00:06:49,743 --> 00:06:53,287
Jesus! That is all you get
for five dollars?

115
00:06:53,288 --> 00:06:54,956
Plus delivery, yes.

116
00:06:54,957 --> 00:06:55,874
[SIGHS]

117
00:06:56,750 --> 00:06:58,251
Lorenz Hart?

118
00:06:58,252 --> 00:07:01,420
You know, I kind of think
I've heard that name before.

119
00:07:01,421 --> 00:07:05,341
You just earned yourself
a dollar tip, kid.

120
00:07:05,342 --> 00:07:07,718
A precedent is being broken.

121
00:07:07,719 --> 00:07:09,220
[CHUCKLES]

122
00:07:09,221 --> 00:07:13,641
Hey, she gave this to me.
Mailed it all the way from New Haven

123
00:07:13,642 --> 00:07:15,977
because I said I wanted something
she'd actually touched.

124
00:07:15,978 --> 00:07:18,355
[SNIFFS] Christ! It's like I'm 17 again,

125
00:07:18,897 --> 00:07:19,981
except I never was 17.

126
00:07:19,982 --> 00:07:23,026
I went directly from childhood
to washed-up.

127
00:07:24,194 --> 00:07:27,489
- Eddie, get the kid a drink, would you?
- No thanks. I'm... I'm working.

128
00:07:28,115 --> 00:07:30,199
Oh, Christ, that's when
you should be drinking.

129
00:07:30,200 --> 00:07:32,410
What's your name? Sven, am I right?

130
00:07:32,411 --> 00:07:35,037
- Troy.
- HART: Ooh, even better.

131
00:07:35,038 --> 00:07:37,039
Listen, Sven, are you free tonight?

132
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:38,917
Eddie, would you get the kid
a goddamn shot?

133
00:07:39,042 --> 00:07:40,209
- Yeah.
- 'Cause I am throwing

134
00:07:40,210 --> 00:07:42,712
an enormous party at my place.

135
00:07:42,713 --> 00:07:44,964
All of show business is going to be there.

136
00:07:44,965 --> 00:07:48,718
I've booked the Golden Gate Quartet.
I'm serious.

137
00:07:48,719 --> 00:07:50,803
I want you to show up, bring a friend,

138
00:07:50,804 --> 00:07:52,096
bring a dozen friends.

139
00:07:52,097 --> 00:07:55,099
It's going to be like
nothing you've ever seen before.

140
00:07:55,100 --> 00:07:59,020
I'm up at the Ardsley, you know?
91st, on the Park.

141
00:07:59,021 --> 00:08:03,232
Just tell the desk clerk
that you're with Lorenz Hart's party.

142
00:08:03,233 --> 00:08:05,193
You're going to need to know the password.

143
00:08:05,194 --> 00:08:07,112
- Are you ready for the password?
- TROY: Mmm-hmm.

144
00:08:10,282 --> 00:08:13,285
"Nobody ever loved me that much."

145
00:08:14,328 --> 00:08:15,704
Slow! Oh.

146
00:08:16,663 --> 00:08:19,081
- Now that is a beautiful sight.
- [COUGHS]

147
00:08:19,082 --> 00:08:20,292
[SNIFFS]

148
00:08:21,668 --> 00:08:22,669
What, you don't drink?

149
00:08:23,253 --> 00:08:25,671
[SINGING]
<i>After one whole quart of brandy</i>

150
00:08:25,672 --> 00:08:28,759
<i>Like a daisy I awake</i>

151
00:08:29,343 --> 00:08:30,509
You know that song?

152
00:08:30,510 --> 00:08:32,220
Uh, no, no.

153
00:08:32,221 --> 00:08:38,017
[SINGING] <i>My funny Valentine
Sweet comic Valentine...</i>

154
00:08:38,018 --> 00:08:40,144
I really don't listen to the radio
that much.

155
00:08:40,145 --> 00:08:41,312
You said you know my name!

156
00:08:41,313 --> 00:08:43,981
- You don't know one Rodgers and Hart song?
- I know...

157
00:08:43,982 --> 00:08:44,899
I just can't really remember...

158
00:08:44,900 --> 00:08:45,900
[SINGING] <i>I'll take Manhattan</i>

159
00:08:45,901 --> 00:08:48,069
<i>The Bronx and Staten...</i>

160
00:08:48,070 --> 00:08:51,239
We were on the cover of <i>Time Magazine!</i>

161
00:08:51,240 --> 00:08:53,992
My picture is on the wall right...

162
00:08:55,077 --> 00:08:57,036
Eddie, where's my picture?

163
00:08:57,037 --> 00:08:58,120
EDDIE: They move 'em around.

164
00:08:58,121 --> 00:09:00,123
- What do you...
- PIANIST: Well, how about this one?

165
00:09:02,709 --> 00:09:04,794
[SINGING] <i>Blue moon</i>

166
00:09:04,795 --> 00:09:06,003
I know that one!

167
00:09:06,004 --> 00:09:09,466
[SINGING ALONG]
<i>You saw me standing alone</i>

168
00:09:10,634 --> 00:09:13,929
<i>Without a dream in my heart</i>

169
00:09:14,596 --> 00:09:17,348
<i>Without a love of my own</i>

170
00:09:17,349 --> 00:09:19,850
Worst goddamn lyric I ever wrote!

171
00:09:19,851 --> 00:09:22,895
- You wrote that?
- Wasn't even supposed to be the title.

172
00:09:22,896 --> 00:09:24,397
[CHUCKLING] I like that song.

173
00:09:24,398 --> 00:09:26,483
HART: Hmm. I'll take my tip back.

174
00:09:29,319 --> 00:09:31,487
I want you at my party, Sven!

175
00:09:31,488 --> 00:09:32,739
[DOOR OPENS]

176
00:09:34,491 --> 00:09:36,492
Doc Bender said to me the other night,

177
00:09:36,493 --> 00:09:39,079
after I told him I'd proposed
to Vivienne again,

178
00:09:39,621 --> 00:09:41,081
"She turned me down, again,"

179
00:09:41,707 --> 00:09:44,500
he said... [IN GRUFF VOICE]
"Larry, make up your mind.

180
00:09:44,501 --> 00:09:46,919
"Are you homosexual or heterosexual?"

181
00:09:46,920 --> 00:09:49,171
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
I said, "Doc, I'm ambisexual."

182
00:09:49,172 --> 00:09:51,007
He said... [IMITATING]
"What the hell does that even mean?"

183
00:09:51,008 --> 00:09:52,758
[IN NORMAL VOICE] I said,
"It means I can jerk off

184
00:09:52,759 --> 00:09:54,552
"equally well with either hand."

185
00:09:54,553 --> 00:09:56,595
Oh, Larry! There's a lady present.

186
00:09:56,596 --> 00:09:59,474
HART: [CHUCKLING]
Well, women can use either hand, too.

187
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:04,270
But to be a writer, you have
to be kind of omni-sexual, don't you?

188
00:10:04,271 --> 00:10:08,357
You have to have, inside yourself,
you know, everyone on earth.

189
00:10:08,358 --> 00:10:10,192
Men, women, horses.

190
00:10:10,193 --> 00:10:13,904
How can you give voice
to the whole chorus of the world

191
00:10:13,905 --> 00:10:17,575
if the whole chorus of the world
isn't already inside you?

192
00:10:17,576 --> 00:10:20,036
[PIANO CONTINUES PLAYING]

193
00:10:20,037 --> 00:10:25,541
Eddie, what do you call a tireless,
relentless homosexual?

194
00:10:25,542 --> 00:10:27,710
- [MUMBLES]
- "Indefagitable."

195
00:10:27,711 --> 00:10:29,587
[CHUCKLING]

196
00:10:29,588 --> 00:10:34,718
To the great and glorious past,
when it all mattered so much.

197
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:37,136
Mmm.

198
00:10:37,137 --> 00:10:38,889
Keep playing. You're good.

199
00:10:39,431 --> 00:10:43,309
- Oh, thank you. I'm an aspiring composer.
- HART: "Aspiring"?

200
00:10:43,310 --> 00:10:45,354
- That means you're breathing, right?
- PIANIST: Mmm.

201
00:10:46,021 --> 00:10:48,939
I better take your name down
in case I need a new partner.

202
00:10:48,940 --> 00:10:51,109
Hey, did you go to the opening tonight?

203
00:10:51,693 --> 00:10:55,363
<i>Oklahoma!</i> With an exclamation point,
no less.

204
00:10:55,364 --> 00:10:58,866
Fact. Any title that feels the need
for an exclamation point,

205
00:10:58,867 --> 00:11:00,619
you want to steer clear of.

206
00:11:01,328 --> 00:11:02,411
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

207
00:11:02,412 --> 00:11:03,996
What did you say
your name was again?

208
00:11:03,997 --> 00:11:07,375
Uh, Morty Rifkin. But I go by the name
of Morty Rafferty.

209
00:11:07,376 --> 00:11:09,961
[SOFTLY] No one could possibly
guess you're Jewish.

210
00:11:10,837 --> 00:11:11,838
[CHUCKLES]

211
00:11:17,636 --> 00:11:18,929
MORTY: Wha'dja think of <i>Oklahoma?</i>

212
00:11:20,263 --> 00:11:23,183
What did I think of <i>Oklahoma?</i>

213
00:11:23,934 --> 00:11:26,394
[INHALES] Well, Knuckles,

214
00:11:26,395 --> 00:11:29,648
Knuckles O'Rifkin,
that's what I'm going to call you,

215
00:11:30,440 --> 00:11:33,234
I saw the show a couple of times
in previews in New Haven,

216
00:11:33,235 --> 00:11:37,279
back when they were still calling it
<i>Away We Go!</i> Exclamation point.

217
00:11:37,280 --> 00:11:40,325
And I felt sure Dick was gonna call me,

218
00:11:41,118 --> 00:11:43,786
"Larry, we're in big trouble.

219
00:11:43,787 --> 00:11:47,456
"I need you to funny up the show.
We need some big comedy numbers."

220
00:11:47,457 --> 00:11:48,916
And I was all ready to say,

221
00:11:48,917 --> 00:11:53,295
"Dick, instead of all this
corn-pone Americana,

222
00:11:53,296 --> 00:11:56,507
"let's do a send-up
of corn-pone Americana!"

223
00:11:56,508 --> 00:11:59,468
I was already writing lyrics in my head.
I couldn't stop.

224
00:11:59,469 --> 00:12:00,719
And did he call you?

225
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:03,807
HART: Are you kidding?
He was too busy writing more hits. Huh.

226
00:12:05,434 --> 00:12:08,394
I sat in my box seat tonight and watched

227
00:12:08,395 --> 00:12:11,230
- "Oklahomo, exclamation point"...
- [EDDIE CHUCKLES]

228
00:12:11,231 --> 00:12:13,732
...down there,
glittering in all its pink lights

229
00:12:13,733 --> 00:12:17,111
and all those cowboy hats
and twirling lassos,

230
00:12:17,112 --> 00:12:21,532
and I knew two things
with absolute certainty.

231
00:12:21,533 --> 00:12:23,492
- [MORTY PLAYS PIANO]
- It was a 14-karat hit

232
00:12:23,493 --> 00:12:26,996
and it was a 14-karat piece of shit.

233
00:12:26,997 --> 00:12:29,373
Oh. Friend of mine saw it in previews,

234
00:12:29,374 --> 00:12:31,334
said it was one of the best shows
he's ever seen.

235
00:12:31,793 --> 00:12:35,754
The show is fraudulent
on every possible level.

236
00:12:35,755 --> 00:12:38,007
And this is not jealousy speaking, okay?

237
00:12:38,008 --> 00:12:44,555
I watched that show tonight
and I felt this great sinking in my heart.

238
00:12:44,556 --> 00:12:49,602
And all around me people are roaring.
They are roaring at third-rate jokes.

239
00:12:49,603 --> 00:12:52,563
I wanted to grab the audience
by the shoulders and say,

240
00:12:52,564 --> 00:12:56,776
"What are you laughing at?
Come on! Demand more!" And...

241
00:12:57,736 --> 00:12:59,653
Rodgers is a genius.

242
00:12:59,654 --> 00:13:02,323
I say that without
one second's hesitation.

243
00:13:02,324 --> 00:13:04,033
You're a piano player.
You know that I'm right.

244
00:13:04,034 --> 00:13:05,243
Yeah, he's pretty good.

245
00:13:05,827 --> 00:13:07,119
Pretty good?

246
00:13:07,120 --> 00:13:11,582
There is no one with his range,
his inventiveness,

247
00:13:11,583 --> 00:13:17,213
great soaring masculine melodies
building like pile drivers.

248
00:13:17,214 --> 00:13:19,465
I mean, Rodgers is a cold-hearted
son of a bitch,

249
00:13:19,466 --> 00:13:21,258
but he can get a melody to levitate,

250
00:13:21,259 --> 00:13:26,013
and that is the hallmark
of great art, levitation.

251
00:13:26,014 --> 00:13:31,310
[SINGING] <i>I've got a beautiful feeling</i>

252
00:13:31,311 --> 00:13:33,730
That's the moment. You hear that?

253
00:13:34,439 --> 00:13:35,773
When your spine glows

254
00:13:35,774 --> 00:13:40,152
and the whole apparatus of songwriting
suddenly breaks free from gravity.

255
00:13:40,153 --> 00:13:44,156
There's maybe five people on the planet
that can pull that off,

256
00:13:44,157 --> 00:13:46,576
and that son of a bitch is one of 'em.

257
00:13:47,452 --> 00:13:53,040
And then, oy... [SIGHS]
Words by Oscar Hammerstein II.

258
00:13:53,041 --> 00:13:54,625
[HART AND EDDIE CHUCKLING]

259
00:13:54,626 --> 00:13:56,460
What can I say about Oscar?

260
00:13:56,461 --> 00:13:58,921
He's going to come striding in here
any second,

261
00:13:58,922 --> 00:14:00,256
all seven and a half feet of him,

262
00:14:00,257 --> 00:14:03,050
and, you know, Dick deliberately went
with somebody tall this time,

263
00:14:03,051 --> 00:14:04,927
you know that. [INHALES DEEPLY]

264
00:14:04,928 --> 00:14:06,512
But what can I say about Oscar?

265
00:14:06,513 --> 00:14:10,057
He's so earthbound,

266
00:14:10,058 --> 00:14:13,394
and let's face it,
most of us are earthbound.

267
00:14:13,395 --> 00:14:15,938
But there are moments, I swear to God,

268
00:14:15,939 --> 00:14:18,023
there are moments in my work

269
00:14:18,024 --> 00:14:20,192
when I have made something bigger
than myself.

270
00:14:20,193 --> 00:14:21,735
I agree, definitely.

271
00:14:21,736 --> 00:14:24,822
Thank you. The words were bigger
than the music,

272
00:14:24,823 --> 00:14:26,574
bigger than the characters
who sang them,

273
00:14:26,575 --> 00:14:30,203
and they approached, for maybe
one-half second, something immortal.

274
00:14:31,204 --> 00:14:34,081
Excuse my limitless self-regard,
but they did,

275
00:14:34,082 --> 00:14:37,126
and if nobody else is going to say it,
then I'm going to.

276
00:14:37,127 --> 00:14:40,462
I have written a handful of words
that are going to cheat death.

277
00:14:40,463 --> 00:14:43,090
Spoken with the modesty of a true lunatic.

278
00:14:43,091 --> 00:14:45,301
Hey! When Shakespeare wrote,

279
00:14:45,302 --> 00:14:47,595
"Not marble nor gilded monuments

280
00:14:47,596 --> 00:14:50,389
"Of princes
shall outlive this powerful rhyme,"

281
00:14:50,390 --> 00:14:53,017
did people say, "My God, what an ego"?

282
00:14:53,018 --> 00:14:57,646
No, they said he is a genius,
and he knows his work is going to last.

283
00:14:57,647 --> 00:14:58,856
So now you're Shakespeare?

284
00:14:58,857 --> 00:15:02,443
Look, <i>Oklahoma!</i> is going to win
the goddamn Pulitzer. I know that.

285
00:15:02,444 --> 00:15:04,820
High schools are going to put it on
from now till doomsday,

286
00:15:04,821 --> 00:15:07,698
because it is so inoffensive.

287
00:15:07,699 --> 00:15:10,909
But really, who wants inoffensive art?

288
00:15:10,910 --> 00:15:12,161
Knuckles... [SNAPS FINGERS]

289
00:15:12,162 --> 00:15:14,330
...are you listening to me?
I'm trying to answer your question.

290
00:15:14,331 --> 00:15:17,416
Is that why God put us on the planet,
to not offend people?

291
00:15:17,417 --> 00:15:20,252
- [CONTINUES PLAYING TUNE]
- The problem with <i>Oklahoma!</i> is this,

292
00:15:20,253 --> 00:15:23,255
and the problem was right there
in the original play,

293
00:15:23,256 --> 00:15:24,923
<i>Green Grow the Fucking Lilacs.</i>

294
00:15:24,924 --> 00:15:27,593
And Dick first showed that play to me,
all right?

295
00:15:27,594 --> 00:15:30,095
He asked me to adapt it first,
and I said no,

296
00:15:30,096 --> 00:15:31,930
and I don't mind that it's nostalgic,

297
00:15:31,931 --> 00:15:33,891
but <i>Oklahoma!,</i> exclamation point,

298
00:15:33,892 --> 00:15:37,186
is nostalgic for a world
that never existed,

299
00:15:37,187 --> 00:15:42,274
and do you really want to write a show
where the main character's name is Curly?

300
00:15:42,275 --> 00:15:44,818
Oh, here's an idea for a song.

301
00:15:44,819 --> 00:15:47,196
"Hey, Moe! Hey, Larry!
I Just Stepped in Cow Shit!"

302
00:15:47,197 --> 00:15:49,282
[MIMICKING THE THREE STOOGES]

303
00:15:50,909 --> 00:15:52,786
[CHUCKLES] I mean, am I bitter?

304
00:15:54,537 --> 00:15:57,123
We write together for a quarter a century,

305
00:15:57,666 --> 00:16:00,668
and the first show
he writes with someone else

306
00:16:00,669 --> 00:16:03,796
is gonna be the biggest hit he ever had.
Am I bitter?

307
00:16:03,797 --> 00:16:05,547
- Larry...
- HART: Fuck yes.

308
00:16:05,548 --> 00:16:09,259
But I need to tell you about Elizabeth.

309
00:16:09,260 --> 00:16:10,636
I need to cleanse my heart.

310
00:16:10,637 --> 00:16:12,137
Here we go. The 20-year-old...

311
00:16:12,138 --> 00:16:14,224
[EXHALES] She's going to come in here
any second.

312
00:16:14,974 --> 00:16:17,101
Uh, Rodgers is gonna
be here tonight, right?

313
00:16:17,102 --> 00:16:20,270
- HART: Don't worry, I'll introduce you.
- Oh, that'd be great.

314
00:16:20,271 --> 00:16:21,980
I'm trying to get somebody
to listen to my songs.

315
00:16:21,981 --> 00:16:24,358
Well, listen and learn.

316
00:16:24,359 --> 00:16:27,612
I'm telling you about Elizabeth.

317
00:16:28,697 --> 00:16:30,782
There's something appealingly...

318
00:16:31,783 --> 00:16:33,951
