And she's talking to me for hours.

712
00:34:59,890 --> 00:35:03,059
Bare leg draped over the armrest.

713
00:35:03,060 --> 00:35:05,603
And I know this sounds like
I'm some middle-aged putz

714
00:35:05,604 --> 00:35:07,146
with a crush on a pretty co-ed,

715
00:35:07,147 --> 00:35:09,106
and maybe that's what it is.

716
00:35:09,107 --> 00:35:10,359
But you know something?

717
00:35:10,943 --> 00:35:15,446
Maybe that's not what it is. [CHUCKLES]

718
00:35:15,447 --> 00:35:18,534
Sometimes I feel... and don't laugh,

719
00:35:19,201 --> 00:35:23,705
after a lifetime of blindly colliding
into strangers,

720
00:35:24,456 --> 00:35:26,041
we've finally found a friend.

721
00:35:27,417 --> 00:35:29,628
Maybe that's the definition
of enchantment.

722
00:35:30,462 --> 00:35:33,840
One light-filled weekend!

723
00:35:33,841 --> 00:35:36,801
I've got to finish telling you this
before she comes back.

724
00:35:36,802 --> 00:35:38,302
Are you listening to me?

725
00:35:38,303 --> 00:35:40,096
Yeah, she got her legs draped over
the thing.

726
00:35:40,097 --> 00:35:42,807
It was as if all the love lyrics
I had ever written

727
00:35:42,808 --> 00:35:47,061
had, like, some sort of verbal ectoplasm,
suddenly taken human form.

728
00:35:47,062 --> 00:35:48,145
- Ecto what?
- [INDISTINCT CHATTER]

729
00:35:48,146 --> 00:35:49,230
That might be her mother.

730
00:35:49,231 --> 00:35:50,774
She cannot hear this.

731
00:35:51,859 --> 00:35:52,984
EDDIE: What about me?

732
00:35:52,985 --> 00:35:54,610
You're just an extra.

733
00:35:54,611 --> 00:35:56,195
Okay, but I still get paid, right?

734
00:35:56,196 --> 00:35:57,948
- HART: Absolutely.
- [CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

735
00:35:58,991 --> 00:36:01,577
It's important to me
that I nail this down.

736
00:36:02,369 --> 00:36:04,704
It was a boiling hot summer weekend,

737
00:36:04,705 --> 00:36:08,332
and I asked, with all the casualness
I could counterfeit,

738
00:36:08,333 --> 00:36:11,961
if she'd like to, you know,
escape the heat of the city,

739
00:36:11,962 --> 00:36:14,672
spend the weekend with me
on Lake Dunmore in Vermont.

740
00:36:14,673 --> 00:36:18,426
And without a moment's hesitation
she said,

741
00:36:18,427 --> 00:36:19,802
[IMITATES ELIZABETH]
"I'd love to, Larry."

742
00:36:19,803 --> 00:36:21,012
[LAUGHS]

743
00:36:21,013 --> 00:36:23,973
Oh, I'm telling you, Andy,
this is my type of girl.

744
00:36:23,974 --> 00:36:26,309
I'm sorry, excuse me, I'm babbling,

745
00:36:26,310 --> 00:36:31,772
but how else do you describe
the actual present tense

746
00:36:31,773 --> 00:36:33,358
of falling in love?

747
00:36:34,610 --> 00:36:35,819
Is that what this is?

748
00:36:36,945 --> 00:36:40,406
Maybe. I mean, I haven't done
anything wrong, okay?

749
00:36:40,407 --> 00:36:44,368
I haven't violated the Mann Act
or even the Middle-Aged Man Act.

750
00:36:44,369 --> 00:36:46,329
I bought her this painting
of Lake Dunmore,

751
00:36:46,330 --> 00:36:48,247
bought it off this old salt Vermonter.

752
00:36:48,248 --> 00:36:51,208
I bought it so that she might remember.

753
00:36:51,209 --> 00:36:53,253
I once did a little canoeing
up around there.

754
00:36:53,962 --> 00:36:55,589
- Hey, Larry!
- [CHUCKLES]

755
00:36:58,383 --> 00:36:59,467
[BREATHES DEEPLY]

756
00:36:59,468 --> 00:37:00,552
And then?

757
00:37:01,428 --> 00:37:04,306
Act Three. Later that day,

758
00:37:05,015 --> 00:37:06,724
she's in the warmth of the cabin.

759
00:37:06,725 --> 00:37:10,102
There's a pennant from Fort Ticonderoga
pinned to the wall.

760
00:37:10,103 --> 00:37:14,774
She's wearing this blue men's work shirt
with the sleeves rolled up.

761
00:37:14,775 --> 00:37:18,569
All of her suddenly available to me,

762
00:37:18,570 --> 00:37:22,406
this gift of youth and brain

763
00:37:22,407 --> 00:37:24,116
and clavicle.

764
00:37:24,117 --> 00:37:26,453
I touched her shoulder,

765
00:37:27,621 --> 00:37:30,247
and as some hack once scribbled,

766
00:37:30,248 --> 00:37:32,209
"My heart stood still."

767
00:37:33,251 --> 00:37:36,213
She took my hand and said, "Larry,

768
00:37:36,880 --> 00:37:39,758
"let's save this for another day."

769
00:37:41,176 --> 00:37:42,885
And all I can tell you, my friend,

770
00:37:42,886 --> 00:37:48,809
is there is a real possibility
that tonight is "another day."

771
00:37:49,851 --> 00:37:51,853
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

772
00:37:53,397 --> 00:37:54,230
[PEOPLE APPLAUDING]

773
00:37:54,231 --> 00:37:57,566
WEEGEE: Clearing back a little bit.
Ladies, beautiful, beautiful!

774
00:37:57,567 --> 00:37:58,651
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

775
00:37:58,652 --> 00:38:01,405
Rodgers! Rodgers!

776
00:38:01,822 --> 00:38:03,073
Yeah, beautiful!

777
00:38:03,824 --> 00:38:04,825
Okay.

778
00:38:05,617 --> 00:38:06,618
- I appreciate that. Thanks.
- [INDISTINCT CHATTERING]

779
00:38:06,827 --> 00:38:07,952
Hey, thank you so much.

780
00:38:07,953 --> 00:38:09,453
I appreciate it. Thank you.

781
00:38:09,454 --> 00:38:10,539
MAN: Bravo!

782
00:38:12,374 --> 00:38:14,542
- OSCAR: Thank you so much.
- [PEOPLE APPLAUDING]

783
00:38:14,543 --> 00:38:17,462
Now, time for the real performance
of the evening.

784
00:38:25,137 --> 00:38:26,220
[BREATH TREMBLING]

785
00:38:26,221 --> 00:38:28,682
Eddie, Eddie. Eddie, get rid of this!

786
00:38:33,228 --> 00:38:34,478
Hey.

787
00:38:34,479 --> 00:38:35,813
So, did he fuck her or not?

788
00:38:35,814 --> 00:38:37,273
He thinks tonight might be the night.

789
00:38:37,274 --> 00:38:41,278
Oh... Larry. Larry, Larry.

790
00:38:41,945 --> 00:38:43,780
What do you think she sees in him?

791
00:38:44,322 --> 00:38:47,451
I think she sees a rich and famous guy
who can help her career.

792
00:38:48,785 --> 00:38:51,162
I think she recognizes she's being adored

793
00:38:51,163 --> 00:38:53,957
by one of the great appreciators
of beauty.

794
00:38:54,875 --> 00:38:57,002
- You know what else I think?
- ANDY: Yeah?

795
00:38:57,919 --> 00:39:00,171
I think she is wearing
a grape-colored brassiere.

796
00:39:00,172 --> 00:39:03,091
All right, Rodgers.
Gentlemen, please let's get one.

797
00:39:03,967 --> 00:39:06,428
Beautiful. Come on. All right, big smile!

798
00:39:07,304 --> 00:39:09,388
- Beautiful.
- Dick! Dick!

799
00:39:09,389 --> 00:39:13,142
My God!
The show is going to run 20 years!

800
00:39:13,143 --> 00:39:15,936
It's going to be bigger
than <i>Abie's Irish Rose!</i>

801
00:39:15,937 --> 00:39:18,773
- We'll see.
- And much more goyish, so it can tour.

802
00:39:18,774 --> 00:39:20,608
[CHUCKLES] Well, thanks for coming, Larry.

803
00:39:20,609 --> 00:39:22,234
- Oh, Oscar!
- Larry.

804
00:39:22,235 --> 00:39:25,071
You get taller
every time I see you. [LAUGHS]

805
00:39:25,072 --> 00:39:27,865
What can I say? The lyrics are brilliant.

806
00:39:27,866 --> 00:39:31,494
Poetic when they need to be poetic,
funny when they need to be funny.

807
00:39:31,495 --> 00:39:34,914
Not a rhyme out of place, easy on the ear.

808
00:39:34,915 --> 00:39:38,042
[SINGING] <i>I'm just a fool
when lights are low</i>

809
00:39:38,043 --> 00:39:40,753
Perfect! [CLAPS AND LAUGHS]
Did you hear me applauding?

810
00:39:40,754 --> 00:39:42,880
I think you were the loudest person
in the entire theater!

811
00:39:42,881 --> 00:39:45,674
That's because I loved it more than
anyone else in the entire theater!

812
00:39:45,675 --> 00:39:47,676
- Let me get you boys a drink.
- RODGERS: Oh, no, thank you.

813
00:39:47,677 --> 00:39:49,887
- Um...
- Larry, you got two minutes?

814
00:39:49,888 --> 00:39:51,138
Give us a minute.

815
00:39:51,139 --> 00:39:52,390
Excuse us, Oscar.

816
00:39:57,604 --> 00:39:58,605
Um...

817
00:40:00,065 --> 00:40:01,315
So, uh, Dwight Wiman and I

818
00:40:01,316 --> 00:40:03,234
have been talking about bringing back
<i>A Connecticut Yankee.</i>

819
00:40:03,235 --> 00:40:04,318
HART: Terrific!

820
00:40:04,319 --> 00:40:06,946
Yeah, I'm thinking of asking
Vivienne Segal.

821
00:40:06,947 --> 00:40:09,949
Oh! <i>Mein Gott!</i> Oh, it's gonna run longer
than <i>Oklahoma!</i>

822
00:40:09,950 --> 00:40:11,659
I'll buy 50 seats myself.

823
00:40:11,660 --> 00:40:14,537
I've got a new title,
[IN SING-SONG VOICE] <i>Ohh, Camelot!</i>

824
00:40:14,538 --> 00:40:15,788
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

825
00:40:15,789 --> 00:40:17,706
Well, I think we're gonna stick with
<i>A Connecticut Yankee.</i>

826
00:40:17,707 --> 00:40:19,500
<i>Camelot Exclamation Point?</i>

827
00:40:19,501 --> 00:40:21,502
[CHUCKLES] Okay, come on.
I'm being serious here.

828
00:40:21,503 --> 00:40:24,004
I'm always serious.
That's why people find me so funny.

829
00:40:24,005 --> 00:40:26,799
So I was thinking, if you feel
up to working, then maybe...

830
00:40:26,800 --> 00:40:28,509
- I've never felt better in my life, Dick.
- Congratulations, Dick.

831
00:40:28,510 --> 00:40:32,012
I don't want to bother you.
I just... We all just loved it.

832
00:40:32,013 --> 00:40:33,347
- RODGERS: Oh, you did?
- It's going to be a big hit.

833
00:40:33,348 --> 00:40:34,640
Oh, thank you. Thank you. Appreciate that.

834
00:40:34,641 --> 00:40:36,142
- It's Gladys, right? Yes.
- Yes! Yeah.

835
00:40:36,143 --> 00:40:38,270
Yes, nice to see you. Um...

836
00:40:40,230 --> 00:40:43,649
Yeah, I was... I was thinking, um,
not just a revival,

837
00:40:43,650 --> 00:40:44,942
I was thinking a whole new book.

838
00:40:44,943 --> 00:40:47,529
We were thinking four or five new numbers.

839
00:40:48,530 --> 00:40:49,572
That I write?

840
00:40:49,573 --> 00:40:51,365
Of course, that you write.
That we write together.

841
00:40:51,366 --> 00:40:53,868
It's been 16 years, you know that,
since we did that show?

842
00:40:53,869 --> 00:40:57,246
- It needs updating, don't you think?
- [LAUGHS] 1927! The Vanderbilt!

843
00:40:57,247 --> 00:40:59,748
Yeah, it can be the new
Rodgers and Hart show for the fall.

844
00:40:59,749 --> 00:41:01,917
- New gags, new songs.
- New references.

845
00:41:01,918 --> 00:41:03,878
[GASPS] We'll satirize the whole war.

846
00:41:03,879 --> 00:41:05,838
Rationing, rubber drives, nylon drives,

847
00:41:05,839 --> 00:41:07,840
a new number for Vivienne.

848
00:41:07,841 --> 00:41:08,966
- Go easy with the satire, Larry.
- Very nice job.

849
00:41:08,967 --> 00:41:10,092
- Hello, nice to see you.
- FAN: Very nice piece.

850
00:41:10,093 --> 00:41:11,177
Appreciate it. Thank you.

851
00:41:11,178 --> 00:41:13,971
[SINGING] <i>There came a lull
then Cordell Hull sent orders from above</i>

852
00:41:13,972 --> 00:41:17,766
<i>I'm sorry, girls, put down your pearls
'Cause now we're rationing love</i>

853
00:41:17,767 --> 00:41:19,268
And how do we get Cordell Hull
into Camelot?

854
00:41:19,269 --> 00:41:20,352
Who cares? It's funny!

855
00:41:20,353 --> 00:41:23,230
Dick! From the <i>New York Journal-American.</i>

856
00:41:23,231 --> 00:41:27,443
"As enchanting to the eye
as Richard Rodgers' music is to the ear."

857
00:41:27,444 --> 00:41:28,527
- Okay.
- Yeah, it's nice.

858
00:41:28,528 --> 00:41:29,695
That's good. Good start.

859
00:41:29,696 --> 00:41:31,780
So, uh, are you up for that?
Are you feeling healthy?

860
00:41:31,781 --> 00:41:33,449
Is that something
you could take seriously?

861
00:41:33,450 --> 00:41:36,243
Yeah. I'm on the wagon, Dick. I'm serious.

862
00:41:36,244 --> 00:41:39,246
[SPUTTERS] Been drinking ginger ale
all night.

863
00:41:39,247 --> 00:41:42,750
Well, except for this second
'cause this second we have to celebrate.

864
00:41:42,751 --> 00:41:45,878
This is the greatest musical
in the history of American theater.

865
00:41:45,879 --> 00:41:48,172
No, no. I'm not drinking with you, Larry.

866
00:41:48,173 --> 00:41:49,757
Okay, okay, all right.

867
00:41:49,758 --> 00:41:51,801
Weegee! Weegee! Shoot this!

868
00:41:53,053 --> 00:41:55,054
- What? Oh, no. Larry, I got to...
- No, no, no. Hey.

869
00:41:55,055 --> 00:41:57,224
Rodgers and Hart, together again!

870
00:41:57,849 --> 00:41:59,851
WEEGEE: All right, closer!
Come on, closer!

871
00:42:03,438 --> 00:42:04,647
I want ten copies of that.

872
00:42:04,648 --> 00:42:06,482
Great. Write me a check.

873
00:42:06,483 --> 00:42:07,900
Yeah.

874
00:42:07,901 --> 00:42:09,276
So, you... you think you're up to that?

875
00:42:09,277 --> 00:42:11,403
It's the best idea I've heard in 16 years.

876
00:42:11,404 --> 00:42:16,075
At the same time, I think we should be
dreaming about something completely new.

877
00:42:16,076 --> 00:42:17,201
Don't you agree?

878
00:42:17,202 --> 00:42:19,328
New Rodgers and Hart,
something people haven't seen before.

879
00:42:19,329 --> 00:42:20,413
Something big!

880
00:42:20,997 --> 00:42:22,331
Let's start with the revival first.

881
00:42:22,332 --> 00:42:24,625
- Absolutely.
- We'll take it one step at a time...

882
00:42:24,626 --> 00:42:26,043
- Yeah, but...
- ...because I really think

883
00:42:26,044 --> 00:42:27,544
- Hear me out.
- ...we can have a future together.

884
00:42:27,545 --> 00:42:29,464
Who doesn't think that?

885
00:42:30,340 --> 00:42:34,760
But I want to be one of those composers
who works with, uh, you know,

886
00:42:34,761 --> 00:42:35,844
other lyricists.

887
00:42:35,845 --> 00:42:37,596
Like Arlen, Kern. You love Kern.

888
00:42:37,597 --> 00:42:39,223
I love Kern. I wanted to be Kern.

889
00:42:39,224 --> 00:42:40,975
But we have to work
like professionals, Larry.

890
00:42:40,976 --> 00:42:42,518
Since when haven't I worked
like a professional?

891
00:42:42,519 --> 00:42:45,437
I want to work at specific times
in the morning, at my office.

892
00:42:45,438 --> 00:42:47,982
- I want to adhere to a schedule.
- Yeah. That's what we do.

893
00:42:47,983 --> 00:42:49,566
I don't want to spend any more time
looking for you, Larry.

894
00:42:49,567 --> 00:42:51,235
- Well, I'm right here. Small as life!
- You know what I mean.

895
00:42:51,236 --> 00:42:52,736
I don't want to be calling up your mother

896
00:42:52,737 --> 00:42:54,196
at nine o'clock in the morning, so that,

897
00:42:54,197 --> 00:42:55,656
maybe, you might
roll out of bed at noon. Right?

898
00:42:55,657 --> 00:42:57,574
- Dick...
- I just don't want to do what we did.

899
00:42:57,575 --> 00:42:59,076
That's all I'm saying.

900
00:42:59,077 --> 00:43:00,620
It's a business, that's all.

901
00:43:01,454 --> 00:43:02,913
Maybe I shouldn't bring it up tonight,
but I don't know,

902
00:43:02,914 --> 00:43:04,623
- I wanted... I wanted to...
- All I want is to...

903
00:43:04,624 --> 00:43:06,292
FAN 1: That was your best one yet.

904
00:43:06,293 --> 00:43:07,918
- Really.
- All right, thank you.

905
00:43:07,919 --> 00:43:09,336
- Who is that?
- All I want is to write a show

906
00:43:09,337 --> 00:43:10,588
we both love.

907
00:43:13,091 --> 00:43:14,091
Yeah, I feel the same way.

908
00:43:14,092 --> 00:43:16,719
Dick! Burns Mantle just called it

909
00:43:16,720 --> 00:43:20,597
"The most thoroughly and attractively
American musical comedy

910
00:43:20,598 --> 00:43:21,682
"since <i>Show Boat."</i>

911
00:43:21,683 --> 00:43:22,891
- Since <i>Show Boat?</i>
- Yeah.

912
00:43:22,892 --> 00:43:24,852
Wow. That's good.

913
00:43:24,853 --> 00:43:26,855
- FAN 2: Truly spectacular.
- Thank you, nice to see you.

914
00:43:27,480 --> 00:43:29,273
I have to fall in love with a show, Dick.

915
00:43:29,274 --> 00:43:31,692
I have to want to write that show
more than anything in the world,

916
00:43:31,693 --> 00:43:35,571
to be in that audience,
sitting there not missing a single word.

917
00:43:35,572 --> 00:43:37,364
All right, well, we start with
<i>A Connecticut Yankee,</i>

918
00:43:37,365 --> 00:43:39,408
- four or five numbers, and we go...
- Okay, look.

919
00:43:39,409 --> 00:43:42,244
Here's what I'm thinking.
<i>The Adventures of Marco Polo.</i>

920
00:43:42,245 --> 00:43:44,455
Dick, Dick! Wonderful show.

921
00:43:44,456 --> 00:43:46,373
Oh, thank you so much. Nice to see you.

922
00:43:46,374 --> 00:43:48,959
Just... just big. Bigger than <i>Jumbo.</i> Epic.

923
00:43:48,960 --> 00:43:51,045
A three-ring musical circus.

924
00:43:51,046 --> 00:43:53,589
The show lasts four hours
with a dinner break!

925
00:43:53,590 --> 00:43:58,469
It's grand comic opera.
And the stage set is the world!

926
00:43:58,470 --> 00:44:01,013
- Uh-huh.
- We satirize everybody.

927
00:44:01,014 --> 00:44:03,098
And you get to satirize them musically.

928
00:44:03,099 --> 00:44:05,601
We send up every national musical cliche
there is.

929
00:44:05,602 --> 00:44:08,187
[IN FRENCH ACCENT] The France number,
[IN ITALIAN ACCENT] the Italian number,

930
00:44:08,188 --> 00:44:10,189
[IN DEEP VOICE] when they get
to the <i>Heart of Darkness,</i>

931
00:44:10,190 --> 00:44:13,025
the cannibals are doing <i>Porgy and Bess.</i>
Boom, boom.

932
00:44:13,026 --> 00:44:15,569
[SINGING] <i>Bess, you is my dinner now!</i>

933
00:44:15,570 --> 00:44:16,653
Jesus, Larry. Come on.

934
00:44:16,654 --> 00:44:19,531
[IN NORMAL VOICE] This show is going
to have the scope of a novel.

935
00:44:19,532 --> 00:44:23,077
It will be the greatest challenge
you've ever had as a composer.

936
00:44:23,078 --> 00:44:27,081
And what grounds it all,
what lets the audience enter this story

937
00:44:27,082 --> 00:44:28,165
is the girl.

938
00:44:28,166 --> 00:44:29,917
- Uh-huh.
- This ethereal girl

939
00:44:29,918 --> 00:44:32,086
whom Marco Polo has left behind.

940
00:44:32,087 --> 00:44:34,421
She's half his age... [CHUCKLES]

941
00:44:34,422 --> 00:44:39,426
...but it's the first time he's felt
that inkling of love in years, maybe ever.

942
00:44:39,427 --> 00:44:40,969
He swears in the first scene.

943
00:44:40,970 --> 00:44:43,097
We set this up like Benedick
in <i>Much Ado...</i>

944
00:44:43,098 --> 00:44:45,349
- Right.
- He swears that he's beyond

945
00:44:45,350 --> 00:44:47,559
the reach of any woman. He scorns love.

946
00:44:47,560 --> 00:44:49,561
And we do a whole number
satirizing love songs.

947
00:44:49,562 --> 00:44:53,399
No. Larry, I want to write shows
that have some emotional core to them...

948
00:44:53,400 --> 00:44:55,818
- Dick, great music. Great show!
- Hello, how are you?

949
00:44:55,819 --> 00:44:57,778
Thank you. I'll take that.
You're a tough critic.

950
00:44:57,779 --> 00:44:58,862
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

951
00:44:58,863 --> 00:45:02,074
Remember, we established
in the first scene that he's anti-love?

952
00:45:02,075 --> 00:45:04,618
Then he meets the girl.
She's a sort of free-spirit,

953
00:45:04,619 --> 00:45:08,414
Scandinavian-looking
with two freckles on her left cheek,

954
00:45:08,415 --> 00:45:10,082
- it's absurd. [LAUGHS]
- Don't do that.

955
00:45:10,083 --> 00:45:13,043
She lives socially,
psychologically, sexually

956
00:45:13,044 --> 00:45:16,965
in another universe than he does,
but he is slain.

957
00:45:17,757 --> 00:45:22,636
He stands there paralyzed
in the light of her pale green eyes.

958
00:45:22,637 --> 00:45:26,306
This is the greatest explorer
in the history of the world,

959
00:45:26,307 --> 00:45:30,894
and none of it means anything to him
unless it's a way to make her see him.

960
00:45:30,895 --> 00:45:34,606
[CHUCKLES] That is the emotional core
of the story.

961
00:45:34,607 --> 00:45:36,316
- Okay.
- We take this legendary,

962
00:45:36,317 --> 00:45:37,526
larger-than-life man,

963
00:45:37,527 --> 00:45:39,153
and we make him bleed.

964
00:45:39,154 --> 00:45:43,532
Mr. Rodgers, my name is Robert Heffner.
I'm the Mayor of Oklahoma City.

965
00:45:43,533 --> 00:45:45,492
Eve and I have traveled
all the way to New York

966
00:45:45,493 --> 00:45:46,785
- just to see the show.
- Okay. You know...

967
00:45:46,786 --> 00:45:49,037
Welcome to New York.
We're finishing a conversation.

968
00:45:49,038 --> 00:45:51,540
He'll be with you in two minutes.
Does that sound good?

969
00:45:51,541 --> 00:45:54,001
Two minutes, I'll be right with you.
Thank you, I hope it was worth it.

970
00:45:54,002 --> 00:45:56,295
- It certainly was.
- Good to see you. Thank you.

971
00:45:56,296 --> 00:45:57,963
All right, so come on.
Come on, come on, come on.

972
00:45:57,964 --> 00:46:00,717
And they end up together? Come on.

973
00:46:01,718 --> 00:46:04,678
That's what the audience
is waiting around to find out!

974
00:46:04,679 --> 00:46:06,472
That's the engine
that's driving the whole story.

975
00:46:06,473 --> 00:46:07,890
All right, well, look, Larry,

976
00:46:07,891 --> 00:46:09,308
if you're willing to write it,

977
00:46:09,309 --> 00:46:11,310
really write it,
and rewrite it, and rewrite it again,

978
00:46:11,311 --> 00:46:12,686
then, you know, it could work.

979
00:46:12,687 --> 00:46:15,230
But I'm not gonna beg you for this, Larry.
You know?

980
00:46:15,231 --> 00:46:16,356
We work for 15 minutes,

981
00:46:16,357 --> 00:46:17,733
you're out the door
looking for a cigar store.

982
00:46:17,734 --> 00:46:18,859
- It drives me...
- [LAUGHING] Okay.

983
00:46:18,860 --> 00:46:20,360
It drives me really crazy.
I don't like it.

984
00:46:20,361 --> 00:46:22,529
- I don't want to do it anymore.
- We've worked like that for 24 years.

985
00:46:22,530 --> 00:46:23,614
Congratulations, Dick!

986
00:46:23,615 --> 00:46:24,781
That's exactly what we've done
for 24 years.

987
00:46:24,782 --> 00:46:26,450
- Thank you.
- About time the Guild had a goddamned hit.

988
00:46:26,451 --> 00:46:28,410
Yeah. You're absolutely, absolutely right.

989
00:46:28,411 --> 00:46:30,579
Anyway, I'm not going to...
I'm not going to fight with you, Larry.

990
00:46:30,580 --> 00:46:32,581
- Who's fighting?
- I don't know.

991
00:46:32,582 --> 00:46:33,665
With a war on,

992
00:46:33,666 --> 00:46:36,668
do audiences really want to watch
cannibals singing <i>Porgy and Bess?</i>

993
00:46:36,669 --> 00:46:38,504
And what do audiences want to watch?

994
00:46:38,505 --> 00:46:41,340
Cowboys a-whoopin'-it-up
at the box social?

995
00:46:41,341 --> 00:46:42,799
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

996
00:46:42,800 --> 00:46:44,468
Well, yes. Apparently.

997
00:46:44,469 --> 00:46:45,802
Oh, that's right, I forgot.

998
00:46:45,803 --> 00:46:49,223
<i>Oklahoma,</i> exclamation point,
addresses the urgency of a nation at war.

999
00:46:49,224 --> 00:46:52,559
I think every serviceman
in that audience tonight

1000
00:46:52,560 --> 00:46:53,894
thought about what we're fighting for,

1001
00:46:53,895 --> 00:46:55,646
even for a second or two,
he thought about it.

1002
00:46:55,647 --> 00:46:57,314
And what is it we're fighting for, exactly?

1003
00:46:57,315 --> 00:47:00,400
Feisty little girls in gingham dresses
who can't say no?

1004
00:47:00,401 --> 00:47:01,735
[HART LAUGHS]

1005
00:47:01,736 --> 00:47:04,154
- Okay. All right.
- Dick, Dick, Dick. Come on.

1006
00:47:04,155 --> 00:47:06,365
Just between you and me,

1007
00:47:06,366 --> 00:47:09,826
those characters are unrecognizable
as human beings.

1008
00:47:09,827 --> 00:47:12,162
I think plenty of people recognized them.
They recognized love.

1009
00:47:12,163 --> 00:47:13,664
He needs rescuing, big time.

1010
00:47:13,665 --> 00:47:16,708
They recognized, uh, family.
They recognized pride in their country.

1011
00:47:16,709 --> 00:47:18,877
You're starting to sound like
<i>Yankee Doodle Dandy.</i>

1012
00:47:18,878 --> 00:47:20,963
I think there's significantly more there
to recognize, Larry,

1013
00:47:20,964 --> 00:47:22,422
than a bunch of singing cannibals.

1014
00:47:22,423 --> 00:47:24,258
But cannibals are much funnier,
admit it.

1015
00:47:24,259 --> 00:47:26,009
OSCAR: Dick, you want to come
and read these!

1016
00:47:26,010 --> 00:47:27,594
- Yeah, hang on! Hang on. Be right there.
- HART: Okay, okay, okay, okay.

1017
00:47:27,595 --> 00:47:30,347
Okay, okay, okay, okay.
I know exactly what you mean.

1018
00:47:30,348 --> 00:47:32,307
Just tell me... What do you
really want to write?

1019
00:47:32,308 --> 00:47:34,142
What's your dream show?

1020
00:47:34,143 --> 00:47:35,227
- My dream show?
- Yeah.

1021
00:47:35,228 --> 00:47:36,521
<i>Oklahoma!</i>

1022
00:47:39,941 --> 00:47:40,942
I mean, next.

1023
00:47:43,194 --> 00:47:46,614
Uh... We're talking about
getting the rights to <i>Liliom.</i>

1024
00:47:48,032 --> 00:47:49,491
- The Molnár play?
- Yeah.

1025
00:47:49,492 --> 00:47:51,285
- That was cornball in 1909.
- Yeah?

1026
00:47:51,286 --> 00:47:53,495
You really want to write a musical
about a carnival barker

1027
00:47:53,496 --> 00:47:55,163
who beats up his girlfriend,

1028
00:47:55,164 --> 00:47:56,999
- dies, comes back...
- I think it'll work.

1029
00:47:57,000 --> 00:47:59,585
Yeah, and at the end, all the dead people
could take off their halos and go,

1030
00:47:59,586 --> 00:48:01,169
"Oh... Purgatory!"

1031
00:48:01,170 --> 00:48:03,505
[LAUGHS] Look,
I will do it if you force me to.

1032
00:48:03,506 --> 00:48:04,923
- It's just in my heart of...
- No, I'm not forcing you to.

1033
00:48:04,924 --> 00:48:06,217
Oscar's going to do it.

1034
00:48:08,469 --> 00:48:11,556
What does Oscar know
about turn-of-the-century Budapest?

1035
00:48:12,390 --> 00:48:14,517
He's going to Americanize it.

1036
00:48:15,310 --> 00:48:16,728
He's going to modernize it.

1037
00:48:17,604 --> 00:48:18,771
We're going to set it in Maine.

1038
00:48:19,355 --> 00:48:22,524
Maine? Right, with all due respect,
modernizing Molnár

1039
00:48:22,525 --> 00:48:24,443
- is a deeply...
- You got to read this!

1040
00:48:24,444 --> 00:48:25,528
Is it the <i>Times?</i>

1041
00:48:26,321 --> 00:48:28,572
Burton Rascoe's <i>World-Telegram</i> review.

1042
00:48:28,573 --> 00:48:29,698
- It's a rave.
- RODGERS: Good.

1043
00:48:29,699 --> 00:48:31,992
- We'll have the <i>Times</i> any moment.
- Okay.

1044
00:48:31,993 --> 00:48:33,869
Larry, I've got to go.
The <i>Times</i> is coming.

1045
00:48:33,870 --> 00:48:34,953
HART: Okay, okay.

1046
00:48:34,954 --> 00:48:37,122
- Wish me luck.
<i>- Mazel tov!</i>

1047
00:48:37,123 --> 00:48:38,374
As they say in Maine.

1048
00:48:39,542 --> 00:48:40,626
[HART CHUCKLES]

1049
00:48:40,627 --> 00:48:42,919
WOMAN: Hey, Dick. That was perfect.
RODGERS: Oh, thank you.

1050
00:48:42,920 --> 00:48:44,588
Nice to see you. Did you enjoy it?

1051
00:48:44,589 --> 00:48:46,382
[PLAYING PIANO]

1052
00:48:50,053 --> 00:48:51,721
[EXHALES]

1053
00:48:59,979 --> 00:49:04,024
What does Dick Rodgers know of Maine?
He was bar-mitzvahed for Christ's sake!

1054
00:49:04,025 --> 00:49:06,318
How long are they going to keep selling
that fairy tale?

1055
00:49:06,319 --> 00:49:09,237
"Have faith, have hope,
the dead will arise to comfort us!"

1056
00:49:09,238 --> 00:49:10,782
Like fuck they will.

1057
00:49:11,282 --> 00:49:13,451
Give me another shot, Eddie. A real one.

1058
00:49:14,577 --> 00:49:15,620
[MOUTHS]

1059
00:49:16,329 --> 00:49:18,539
Join me for a shot, Andy? Please.

1060
00:49:21,751 --> 00:49:22,752
[HART SIGHS]

1061
00:49:23,503 --> 00:49:24,837
How ya holding up?

1062
00:49:25,797 --> 00:49:29,216
HART: You know how in a marriage they say
"for better or for worse"?

1063
00:49:29,217 --> 00:49:32,928
I think in terms of my life,
I've entered the "for worse" part.

1064
00:49:32,929 --> 00:49:37,391
And it happened so quietly
I didn't even recognize it.

1065
00:49:37,392 --> 00:49:38,685
Have you ever felt that way?

1066
00:49:39,560 --> 00:49:41,062
Every day of my life.

1067
00:49:43,356 --> 00:49:44,815
[SOFTLY] Thank you.

1068
00:49:44,816 --> 00:49:46,983
Sometimes I think,
"Even God is finished with me."

1069
00:49:46,984 --> 00:49:48,568
I've had my hits,

1070
00:49:48,569 --> 00:49:51,697
I've loved a small,
dear collection of people.

1071
00:49:51,698 --> 00:49:53,657
And now he's turned the page.

1072
00:49:53,658 --> 00:49:55,827
[CHUCKLES] I feel superannuated.

1073
00:49:56,661 --> 00:49:59,204
"Superannuated."
That's a good thing, isn't it?

1074
00:49:59,205 --> 00:50:00,957
It means your dick doesn't work.

1075
00:50:02,709 --> 00:50:04,627
- Must be why I don't know that word.
- HART: Hmm.

1076
00:50:07,922 --> 00:50:09,298
Put me on the list.

1077
00:50:10,383 --> 00:50:11,426
[CHUCKLES]

1078
00:50:20,226 --> 00:50:22,395
You notice the birds
are back in Central Park?

1079
00:50:23,563 --> 00:50:26,314
Hmm. What are you working on these days?

1080
00:50:26,315 --> 00:50:27,942
Children's book.

1081
00:50:29,068 --> 00:50:31,069
Must have burned myself out
writing those essays,

1082
00:50:31,070 --> 00:50:32,155
it's not going well.

1083
00:50:33,197 --> 00:50:34,698
I think, as far as my writing goes,

1084
00:50:34,699 --> 00:50:36,533
I've also entered the "for worse" part.

1085
00:50:36,534 --> 00:50:38,785
HART: [CHUCKLES]
What's your story about?

1086
00:50:38,786 --> 00:50:40,204
I wish I knew.

1087
00:50:41,539 --> 00:50:43,291
The journey everybody takes?

1088
00:50:44,625 --> 00:50:48,087
Searching for what's perfect
and unattainable?

1089
00:50:48,838 --> 00:50:49,881
The ineffable!

1090
00:50:50,465 --> 00:50:53,508
Probably too elusive an idea
to put into a children's book.

1091
00:50:53,509 --> 00:50:54,969
I have a line for you.

1092
00:50:56,262 --> 00:50:59,931
"He chased her around the bed all night
before concluding

1093
00:50:59,932 --> 00:51:01,308
"she was ineffable."

1094
00:51:01,309 --> 00:51:03,019
Sure you don't mean "uneffable"?

1095
00:51:03,561 --> 00:51:05,396
[CLICKS TONGUE] Better.

1096
00:51:05,980 --> 00:51:07,356
[HART CHUCKLES]

1097
00:51:08,191 --> 00:51:09,483
You know, I'm in the park every morning,

1098
00:51:09,484 --> 00:51:11,943
liberating this mouse
I keep catching in my kitchen.

1099
00:51:11,944 --> 00:51:14,696
- Yeah?
- I have this little glass box

1100
00:51:14,697 --> 00:51:17,532
that captures the mouse
but doesn't kill him.

1101
00:51:17,533 --> 00:51:19,701
And every morning I walk into my kitchen,

1102
00:51:19,702 --> 00:51:21,912
and there he is,
at the bottom of the refrigerator.

1103
00:51:21,913 --> 00:51:25,832
My little brown mouse,
happily eating the cracker I left for him.

1104
00:51:25,833 --> 00:51:28,210
And every morning,
I carry him down to the park,

1105
00:51:28,211 --> 00:51:31,713
open the box. He leaps out ten feet,
scurries into the underbrush.

1106
00:51:31,714 --> 00:51:34,633
And then the next morning, I'll be damned,

1107
00:51:34,634 --> 00:51:36,802
he is back in the box!

1108
00:51:36,803 --> 00:51:38,470
How do you know it's the same mouse?

1109
00:51:38,471 --> 00:51:39,554
Well, he certainly looks the same.

1110
00:51:39,555 --> 00:51:43,935
He has that same New York look
of doomed hopefulness.

1111
00:51:44,977 --> 00:51:48,105
But how does he get up the 19 floors?

1112
00:51:49,398 --> 00:51:50,774
Maybe he's tipping the doorman.

1113
00:51:50,775 --> 00:51:51,943
[HART CHUCKLES]

1114
00:51:53,528 --> 00:51:55,279
You know, this morning he wasn't there.

1115
00:51:55,947 --> 00:51:59,116
Just the cracker lying in the box.

1116
00:52:00,201 --> 00:52:02,118
I actually missed the little fella,
I really did.

1117
00:52:02,119 --> 00:52:04,412
I think I've started to identify with him.

1118
00:52:04,413 --> 00:52:06,290
Does he have a name?

1119
00:52:07,291 --> 00:52:09,042
I'm calling him Stuart.

1120
00:52:09,043 --> 00:52:11,212
- [CHUCKLES]
- With a "W" or a "U"?

1121
00:52:12,213 --> 00:52:16,842
Hmm. A "U." Nothing fancy.
Just a regular middle-class mouse.

1122
00:52:16,843 --> 00:52:18,928
[PEOPLE CHEERING]

1123
00:52:20,680 --> 00:52:22,889
I think you'll have to excuse me.

1124
00:52:22,890 --> 00:52:26,185
All this jubilation
has gone to my bladder.

1125
00:52:29,313 --> 00:52:32,065
LANGNER: "Agnes de Mille
works small miracles

1126
00:52:32,066 --> 00:52:36,361
"and devising original dances
that fit the story and the tunes.

1127
00:52:36,362 --> 00:52:38,530
<i>"Oklahoma!</i> is fresh..."

1128
00:52:38,531 --> 00:52:40,740
- Okay, I got something funny.
- Hmm.

1129
00:52:40,741 --> 00:52:43,243
What do you call a tired homosexual?

1130
00:52:43,244 --> 00:52:45,246
- [INDISTINCT CHATTER]
- I don't know.

1131
00:52:47,498 --> 00:52:48,708
Fuck, I forgot.

1132
00:52:49,500 --> 00:52:50,793
That's really funny.

1133
00:52:51,294 --> 00:52:52,169
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

1134
00:52:52,920 --> 00:52:56,464
LANGNER: "The play's spine-tingling,
out of this world!"

1135
00:52:56,465 --> 00:52:58,384
[PEOPLE CHEERING]

1136
00:53:01,429 --> 00:53:02,430
[TOILET FLUSHING]

1137
00:53:04,432 --> 00:53:07,894
HART: You know, when Atkinson wrote that
review for <i>Pal Joey,</i> you remember that?

1138
00:53:08,561 --> 00:53:10,729
"Drab and mirthless.

1139
00:53:10,730 --> 00:53:14,317
"Can one draw sweet water
from a foul well?"

1140
00:53:15,401 --> 00:53:18,653
I cried. [CHUCKLES] That's how hurt I was.

1141
00:53:18,654 --> 00:53:22,324
I cried in Vivienne Segal's arms.

1142
00:53:22,325 --> 00:53:23,825
She hugged me and said,

1143
00:53:23,826 --> 00:53:27,537
"History is going to prove him wrong,
darling."

1144
00:53:27,538 --> 00:53:29,456
Wasn't that
the sweetest thing in the world

1145
00:53:29,457 --> 00:53:30,708
for someone to say?

1146
00:53:32,126 --> 00:53:34,045
And she actually calls me "darling." Hmph.

1147
00:53:34,629 --> 00:53:36,004
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY] Wow.

1148
00:53:36,005 --> 00:53:37,339
<i>Time</i> magazine wrote,

1149
00:53:37,340 --> 00:53:39,549
"For those who can park their morals
in the lobby,

1150
00:53:39,550 --> 00:53:41,177
<i>"Pal Joey</i> is a wow."

1151
00:53:42,178 --> 00:53:44,639
What kind of piece-of-shit praise is that?

1152
00:53:46,432 --> 00:53:49,434
- [SNIFFLES] I'm talking about <i>Pal Joey.</i>
- Right.

1153
00:53:49,435 --> 00:53:50,645
I didn't see that one.

1154
00:53:51,270 --> 00:53:54,565
Wolcott Gibbs, he loved the show.

1155
00:53:55,149 --> 00:53:57,692
He said it was,
"A song and dance production

1156
00:53:57,693 --> 00:54:01,279
"with living three-dimensional figures,

1157
00:54:01,280 --> 00:54:04,866
"talking and behaving like human beings."

1158
00:54:04,867 --> 00:54:07,203
- Ah, see? There you go.
- Mmm-hmm.

1159
00:54:08,412 --> 00:54:10,622
You're still going to introduce me
to Rodgers tonight, right?

1160
00:54:10,623 --> 00:54:13,875
Urination for me
has turned into a two-act play

1161
00:54:13,876 --> 00:54:15,251
with a brief intermission.

1162
00:54:15,252 --> 00:54:17,046
[BOTH LAUGHING]

1163
00:54:18,798 --> 00:54:23,427
Oh, I love Vivienne. God help me. [LAUGHS]

1164
00:54:24,095 --> 00:54:25,554
Her compassion.

1165
00:54:26,555 --> 00:54:28,057
Oh, did I tell you she calls me "darling"?

1166
00:54:28,975 --> 00:54:31,351
We were up at the Starlight Roof.

1167
00:54:31,352 --> 00:54:36,523
I turned to her and I said,
"Vivienne, will you please marry me?"

1168
00:54:36,524 --> 00:54:39,317
That's what I told her. Right to her face.

1169
00:54:39,318 --> 00:54:42,989
Can you imagine having the courage
to say that to a woman?

1170
00:54:43,781 --> 00:54:46,032
I've never had the courage
to even dream of saying that.

1171
00:54:46,033 --> 00:54:47,617
Mmm-hmm. Yeah. It was a moment.

1172
00:54:47,618 --> 00:54:52,665
Let me tell you. 2:00 a.m., the band
was playing <i>I've Heard That Song Before.</i>

1173
00:54:53,374 --> 00:54:56,419
She said, "I love you, darling,

1174
00:54:57,211 --> 00:54:58,713
"just not that way."

1175
00:55:01,007 --> 00:55:03,426
"Not that way."

1176
00:55:04,051 --> 00:55:06,678
Three little words.

1177
00:55:06,679 --> 00:55:10,307
Ten little letters that mean,

1178
00:55:11,058 --> 00:55:13,894
"Game over, schmuck." [LAUGHS]

1179
00:55:14,770 --> 00:55:17,564
Ah, "Think it over," I told her.

1180
00:55:17,565 --> 00:55:21,818
I took her hand in mine,
her nail polish was pale gray...

1181
00:55:21,819 --> 00:55:22,903
[DOOR CLOSES]

1182
00:55:27,616 --> 00:55:31,494
- [INDISTINCT CHATTER]
- Now... I can drink.

1183
00:55:31,495 --> 00:55:34,497
[ALL CHEERING]

1184
00:55:34,498 --> 00:55:38,334
May I remind everybody what Mike Todd
said about <i>Oklahoma!</i> in New Haven,

1185
00:55:38,335 --> 00:55:41,713
- "No laughs, no tits, no chance"?
- [ALL LAUGHING]

1186
00:55:41,714 --> 00:55:45,051
We have a chance now.
All right, read that out. Okay, wow.

1187
00:55:45,843 --> 00:55:48,803
LANGNER: Wonderful. This is what
Nichols said in the <i>Times.</i>

1188
00:55:48,804 --> 00:55:51,306
"Wonderful is the nearest adjective,

1189
00:55:51,307 --> 00:55:53,349
"for this excursion of the Guild

1190
00:55:53,350 --> 00:55:57,312
"combines a fresh and infectious gaiety,
a charm of manner,

1191
00:55:57,313 --> 00:55:59,773
"beautiful acting, dancing and singing,

1192
00:55:59,774 --> 00:56:04,277
"and a score by Richard Rodgers
which doesn't do any harm either,

1193
00:56:04,278 --> 00:56:06,821
"since it is one of his best.

1194
00:56:06,822 --> 00:56:08,908
[ALL CHEERING]

1195
00:56:12,203 --> 00:56:15,872
"Mr. Rodgers's scores never lack grace,

1196
00:56:15,873 --> 00:56:21,294
"but seldom have they been
so well-integrated as this for <i>Oklahoma!</i>

1197
00:56:21,295 --> 00:56:27,342
"He has turned out waltzes, love songs,
comic songs and a title number

1198
00:56:27,343 --> 00:56:30,804
"which the State in question
would do well to adopt

1199
00:56:30,805 --> 00:56:32,514
"as its anthem forthwith.

1200
00:56:32,515 --> 00:56:34,517
[PEOPLE CHEERING]

1201
00:56:37,228 --> 00:56:41,189
"<i>Oh, What a Beautiful Morning,</i>
and <i>People Will Say We're in Love</i>

1202
00:56:41,190 --> 00:56:44,609
"are headed for countless jukeboxes
across the land.

1203
00:56:44,610 --> 00:56:46,695
[ALL CHEERING]

1204
00:56:47,863 --> 00:56:52,700
"And a dirge called 'Pore Jud',
in which the hero of the fable

1205
00:56:52,701 --> 00:56:55,870
"tries to persuade his rival
to hang himself

1206
00:56:55,871 --> 00:56:58,748
- is amazingly comic.
- [ALL LAUGHING]

1207
00:56:58,749 --> 00:57:03,419
<i>"The Farmer and the Cowman</i>
and <i>The Surrey with the Fringe on the Top</i>

1208
00:57:03,420 --> 00:57:09,592
"also deserve mention only because
they quite clearly approach perfection."

1209
00:57:09,593 --> 00:57:11,053
- [ALL APPLAUDING]
- Read that part again.

1210
00:57:12,763 --> 00:57:16,307
"...because they quite clearly
approach perfection."

1211
00:57:16,308 --> 00:57:17,977
Put that on the marquee!

1212
00:57:18,561 --> 00:57:21,187
"Quite clearly approaches perfection."

1213
00:57:21,188 --> 00:57:23,065
[ALL CHEERING]

1214
00:57:24,400 --> 00:57:28,444
Come on, everybody! Party upstairs!
Cake and champagne.

1215
00:57:28,445 --> 00:57:30,029
[ALL CHEERING]

1216
00:57:30,030 --> 00:57:31,489
[PIANO MUSIC PLAYING]

1217
00:57:31,490 --> 00:57:33,534
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1218
00:57:38,873 --> 00:57:41,332
Oh, Oscar! Bravo, bravo.

1219
00:57:41,333 --> 00:57:43,377
Congratulations. Oh...
[HESITATING]

1220
00:57:48,883 --> 00:57:50,383
Can I speak with you for a moment?

1221
00:57:50,384 --> 00:57:51,467
Can we talk later, Larry?

1222
00:57:51,468 --> 00:57:54,012
No, no, no. It's just a second.
I have something important to say.

1223
00:57:54,013 --> 00:57:55,930
Just a moment with the musical genius.

1224
00:57:55,931 --> 00:57:57,183
[HART CHUCKLES]

1225
00:57:58,684 --> 00:58:01,811
I just have one thing
I want to tell you, Dick.

1226
00:58:01,812 --> 00:58:06,025
Uh... Just one second, Dick.
It's important.

1227
00:58:06,650 --> 00:58:08,443
I remember when I first heard about you,

1228
00:58:08,444 --> 00:58:11,154
you were just Morty Rodger's
little brother.

1229
00:58:11,155 --> 00:58:13,239
- What, were you 17?
- 16.

1230
00:58:13,240 --> 00:58:14,866
- Yeah, I was 23.
- Swell job.

1231
00:58:14,867 --> 00:58:16,409
Yeah, you were the wise old man
on the mountain.

1232
00:58:16,410 --> 00:58:18,620
But when I first heard you
play your stuff,

1233
00:58:18,621 --> 00:58:21,497
I knew you had it.

1234
00:58:21,498 --> 00:58:23,458
I wasn't entirely convinced that I had it,

1235
00:58:23,459 --> 00:58:26,003
but I heard something that afternoon.

1236
00:58:28,047 --> 00:58:31,300
Originality, melody, grace...

1237
00:58:32,760 --> 00:58:34,385
- Oh... [BREATH TREMBLING]
- [LAUGHS]

1238
00:58:34,386 --> 00:58:37,847
Come on. Come on, Larry. Stop it.
Come on, what's the matter with you?

1239
00:58:37,848 --> 00:58:41,726
You worked your whole life
for this night, Dick.

1240
00:58:41,727 --> 00:58:44,687
Nobody's worked harder.
And nobody deserves it more.

1241
00:58:44,688 --> 00:58:46,481
All right, thanks. Thanks, Larry.
Thank you.

1242
00:58:46,482 --> 00:58:49,108
All right, that's what I wanted...
Just go...

1243
00:58:49,109 --> 00:58:50,985
[SNIFFLES AND LAUGHS]
...enjoy your party.

1244
00:58:50,986 --> 00:58:52,779
- Hey, look at me. Look at me.
- Mmm-hmm?

1245
00:58:52,780 --> 00:58:55,114
We're going to do
<i>A Connecticut Yankee,</i> all new.

1246
00:58:55,115 --> 00:58:57,242
- Yeah, yeah.
- We're gonna write four or five new songs.

1247
00:58:57,243 --> 00:58:58,576
- I have ideas already.
- Right?

1248
00:58:58,577 --> 00:59:01,204
Yeah, yeah. And if I get some pages down
for Marco Polo,

1249
00:59:01,205 --> 00:59:02,289
can I send them over?

1250
00:59:03,707 --> 00:59:07,670
You have to ask me that?
Larry, I owe my professional life to you.

1251
00:59:11,298 --> 00:59:14,801
[SINGING] <i>Summer journeys to Niagara
And to other places</i>

1252
00:59:14,802 --> 00:59:17,679
<i>Aggravate all our cares...</i>

1253
00:59:17,680 --> 00:59:19,597
You remember we heard that on the radio
for the first time?

1254
00:59:19,598 --> 00:59:22,267
In your parents' living room.
Our first hit.

1255
00:59:22,268 --> 00:59:25,061
That was one of the most
astonishing moments of my life, Larry.

1256
00:59:25,062 --> 00:59:29,023
- I was 22.
- And I'm telling you, I swear to God,

1257
00:59:29,024 --> 00:59:31,526
our best work is still ahead of us.

1258
00:59:31,527 --> 00:59:33,611
Yes, the new <i>Connecticut Yankee!</i>

1259
00:59:33,612 --> 00:59:35,238
Yeah, yeah. And bigger stuff.

1260
00:59:35,239 --> 00:59:37,156
- MAN: Dick, get up here.
- All right. I'm coming!

1261
00:59:37,157 --> 00:59:39,618
I mean, Marco Polo is going to be
a show about joy...

1262
00:59:40,286 --> 00:59:44,039
but a hard-earned joy,
an unsentimental joy.

1263
00:59:44,915 --> 00:59:47,251
- Something wrong with sentimental?
- What? It's too easy.

1264
00:59:50,296 --> 00:59:52,047
<i>- Oklahoma!</i> is too easy?
- [SPUTTERS]

1265
00:59:52,798 --> 00:59:55,174
The guy actually getting the girl
at the end is too easy?

1266
00:59:55,175 --> 00:59:57,885
You've just eliminated
every successful musical comedy...

1267
00:59:57,886 --> 00:59:59,095
- [CHUCKLES]
- ...ever written, Larry.

1268
00:59:59,096 --> 01:00:00,179
Then it's too easy for me.

1269
01:00:00,180 --> 01:00:01,598
Did you hear the audience tonight?

1270
01:00:02,224 --> 01:00:03,225
Yes.

1271
01:00:04,268 --> 01:00:06,644
Sixteen hundred people
didn't think it was too easy.

1272
01:00:06,645 --> 01:00:08,479
You're telling me 1,600 people are wrong?

1273
01:00:08,480 --> 01:00:09,940
I'm just saying...

1274
01:00:11,066 --> 01:00:17,071
that you and I can do something
so much more emotionally complicated.

1275
01:00:17,072 --> 01:00:19,282
We don't have to pander
to what audiences...

1276
01:00:19,283 --> 01:00:21,326
- Oscar and I are pandering?
- No. I didn't say that.

1277
01:00:21,327 --> 01:00:23,578
- Irving Berlin is pandering?
- I love Berlin.

1278
01:00:23,579 --> 01:00:26,331
<i>- White Christmas</i> is pandering?
- Well, I don't believe <i>White Christmas.</i>

1279
01:00:26,332 --> 01:00:28,416
- Okay.
- [BOTH CHUCKLE]

1280
01:00:28,417 --> 01:00:30,209
Well, maybe audiences have changed.

1281
01:00:30,210 --> 01:00:32,128
Well, they still want to laugh.

1282
01:00:32,129 --> 01:00:33,921
They want to laugh, but not in that way.

1283
01:00:33,922 --> 01:00:35,507
- Not in what way?
- In your way.

1284
01:00:36,592 --> 01:00:38,426
They want to laugh,
but they also want to cry a little.

1285
01:00:38,427 --> 01:00:41,346
They want to... they want to feel.

1286
01:00:41,347 --> 01:00:42,389
HART: Hmm.

1287
01:00:44,641 --> 01:00:46,392
You're my oldest friend.

1288
01:00:46,393 --> 01:00:49,229
- [SIGHS WEARILY]
- [HESITATING] You're...

1289
01:00:50,522 --> 01:00:52,398
- you're unique.
- Hmm.

1290
01:00:52,399 --> 01:00:53,984
Sounds like you're writing my obituary.

1291
01:00:54,985 --> 01:00:57,862
- I'm just saying.
- I'm right here, right now.

1292
01:00:57,863 --> 01:01:00,865
- Ready to work.
- Yeah?

1293
01:01:00,866 --> 01:01:02,200
HART: Hmm.

1294
01:01:02,201 --> 01:01:04,536
And you're willing to go
back to Doctors Hospital?

1295
01:01:05,662 --> 01:01:08,331
I don't need to go back
to Doctors Hospital,

1296
01:01:08,332 --> 01:01:11,584
and I don't need a psychiatrist either.

1297
01:01:11,585 --> 01:01:13,628
- Thank you very much.
- We were just trying to help you, Larry.

1298
01:01:13,629 --> 01:01:15,797
Who's we? You and Oscar? Help me?

1299
01:01:15,798 --> 01:01:17,298
Oscar? You think Oscar
had anything to do with it?

1300
01:01:17,299 --> 01:01:20,718
<i>Oklahoma!</i> is going to be the biggest hit
of your career.

1301
01:01:20,719 --> 01:01:23,096
- You don't know that. You don't know that.
- You got that asshole Kron

1302
01:01:23,097 --> 01:01:25,056
to manage my money.
Now I'm incapable...

1303
01:01:25,057 --> 01:01:26,849
I did that at the insistence
of your brother, Larry.

1304
01:01:26,850 --> 01:01:27,934
Teddy literally begged me...

1305
01:01:27,935 --> 01:01:30,186
Well, maybe you and Teddy
should write the lyrics.

1306
01:01:30,187 --> 01:01:31,813
I did write the lyrics.

1307
01:01:31,814 --> 01:01:32,814
[LAUGHS SARCASTICALLY]

1308
01:01:32,815 --> 01:01:34,023
What is that supposed to mean?

1309
01:01:34,024 --> 01:01:36,859
<i>By Jupiter?</i> Have you conveniently
blocked that out?

1310
01:01:36,860 --> 01:01:38,152
Blocked what out?

1311
01:01:38,153 --> 01:01:41,614
How Logan and I begged you
for extra choruses, extra verses,

1312
01:01:41,615 --> 01:01:44,784
and you were so drunk
that you didn't even show up.

1313
01:01:44,785 --> 01:01:46,619
So, yes, I had to write the lyrics.

1314
01:01:46,620 --> 01:01:49,497
- You didn't write one fucking word...
- How would you know?

1315
01:01:49,498 --> 01:01:51,207
- ...of that show.
- How would you know, Larry?

1316
01:01:51,208 --> 01:01:53,000
You weren't around to even...

1317
01:01:53,001 --> 01:01:54,085
You know what?

1318
01:01:54,086 --> 01:01:56,129
I'm actually not going to argue
with you tonight,

1319
01:01:56,130 --> 01:01:57,255
- if that's all right with you.
- I like to argue.

1320
01:01:57,256 --> 01:01:59,090
Well I don't. I don't.

1321
01:01:59,091 --> 01:02:00,467
Look, I am sorry.

1322
01:02:01,510 --> 01:02:04,095
I don't care if somebody attacks me.

1323
01:02:04,096 --> 01:02:06,389
It doesn't mean anything to me.

1324
01:02:06,390 --> 01:02:10,268
But nobody can attack my work.
It is all I've got.

1325
01:02:10,269 --> 01:02:12,271
Your work is brilliant.
That's not the problem.

1326
01:02:15,274 --> 01:02:18,652
Your work has been brilliant
since the day I met you.

1327
01:02:19,903 --> 01:02:21,238
Do you still remember that?

1328
01:02:22,322 --> 01:02:24,699
You, standing there in your
carpet slippers and your stripy bathrobe?

1329
01:02:24,700 --> 01:02:25,701
[HART CHUCKLES]

1330
01:02:26,618 --> 01:02:30,872
Yeah, with the five o'clock shadow
at 11:00 a.m.

1331
01:02:30,873 --> 01:02:33,291
[BOTH CHUCKLING]

1332
01:02:33,292 --> 01:02:36,462
I'll remember that
till the last day of my life.

1333
01:02:39,298 --> 01:02:41,091
[INHALES DEEPLY] Okay.

1334
01:02:44,052 --> 01:02:45,262
[SIGHS]

1335
01:02:46,680 --> 01:02:47,681
[LAUGHS]

1336
01:02:48,265 --> 01:02:49,348
- Larry, I got to go upstairs.
- I know.

1337
01:02:49,349 --> 01:02:51,518
- The whole company's waiting.
- Of course. Of course.

1338
01:02:53,103 --> 01:02:54,604
Four or five songs, yes?

1339
01:02:54,605 --> 01:02:56,732
I'm telling you, I'm having ideas already!

1340
01:02:57,774 --> 01:02:59,775
A big comedy solo for Vivienne

1341
01:02:59,776 --> 01:03:03,572
about how she's killed off
every single one of her previous husbands.

1342
01:03:04,948 --> 01:03:05,948
Might be funny.

1343
01:03:05,949 --> 01:03:08,827
We can call it <i>To Keep Our Love Alive!</i>

1344
01:03:21,924 --> 01:03:22,883
[GIGGLES]

1345
01:03:23,884 --> 01:03:25,594
- You okay, Larry?
- Mmm-hmm.

1346
01:03:30,474 --> 01:03:31,599
What happened to White?

1347
01:03:31,600 --> 01:03:34,019
- Left.
- "So soon?"

1348
01:03:34,561 --> 01:03:36,979
There was so much more
I wanted to say to him.

1349
01:03:36,980 --> 01:03:38,982
- Maybe he was an extra, too.
- [SIGHS SOFTLY]

1350
01:03:39,942 --> 01:03:40,984
One more?

1351
01:03:41,860 --> 01:03:42,945
Last one, Larry.

1352
01:03:45,030 --> 01:03:47,658
Do you know the ineffectual blues?

1353
01:03:49,993 --> 01:03:52,078
That's because I haven't written it yet.

1354
01:03:52,079 --> 01:03:53,664
[CHUCKLES]

1355
01:03:54,957 --> 01:03:58,417
[SIGHS] They should put
my picture on that bottle.

1356
01:03:58,418 --> 01:04:02,547
"The Whiskey That Made
Lorenz Hart Unemployable."

1357
01:04:02,548 --> 01:04:04,508
[SCOFFS] "Buy War Bonds."

1358
01:04:09,638 --> 01:04:11,055
[EXHALES]

1359
01:04:11,056 --> 01:04:13,641
You know, I've started
to hear things wrong.

1360
01:04:13,642 --> 01:04:16,727
The other night,
I was listening to this singer go on

1361
01:04:16,728 --> 01:04:18,397
about "her cigarette heart."

1362
01:04:18,939 --> 01:04:21,857
And I thought,
"Now that is an original metaphor,

1363
01:04:21,858 --> 01:04:23,569
"'My cigarette heart.'"

1364
01:04:24,278 --> 01:04:26,738
Then I realized she was singing
"My secret heart."

1365
01:04:27,531 --> 01:04:30,408
I can't remember anything anymore either.

1366
01:04:30,409 --> 01:04:32,952
That should be the title
of my autobiography,

1367
01:04:32,953 --> 01:04:35,539
"Stop Me If I've Told You This Already."

1368
01:04:36,206 --> 01:04:39,084
And we'll print the entire text twice.
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

1369
01:04:45,549 --> 01:04:47,883
ELIZABETH: No, I'm serious.
I've seen her do it before.

1370
01:04:47,884 --> 01:04:50,804
GEORGE: As long as there's
no dancing later on in the night.

1371
01:04:51,346 --> 01:04:52,430
[CHUCKLING]

1372
01:04:52,431 --> 01:04:54,098
ELIZABETH: You better watch yourself...

1373
01:04:54,099 --> 01:04:57,018
My irreplaceable Elizabeth!

1374
01:04:57,019 --> 01:04:58,103
Larry!

1375
01:04:59,062 --> 01:05:00,896
- Do you like it?
- HART: It's...

1376
01:05:00,897 --> 01:05:02,941
Oscar Hammerstein just said I was a gem!

1377
01:05:03,609 --> 01:05:06,445
He has such a way with words.

1378
01:05:07,195 --> 01:05:09,113
George, this is Lorenz Hart.

1379
01:05:09,114 --> 01:05:11,490
I am legitimately honored to meet you.

1380
01:05:11,491 --> 01:05:15,036
Would you mind if I spoke to Elizabeth
alone for two minutes?

1381
01:05:15,037 --> 01:05:16,787
And then she's all yours.

1382
01:05:16,788 --> 01:05:18,039
It would be perfectly all right

1383
01:05:18,040 --> 01:05:20,916
as long as you promise me
your autograph before I go.

1384
01:05:20,917 --> 01:05:22,294
ELIZABETH: George is a senior at Yale.

1385
01:05:22,419 --> 01:05:24,921
He's studying music,
but he wants to be a director.

1386
01:05:25,047 --> 01:05:26,464
A director. Well, what's your name?

1387
01:05:26,465 --> 01:05:27,548
George Hill.

1388
01:05:27,549 --> 01:05:31,552
Here's my advice to you,
future director, George Hill.

1389
01:05:31,553 --> 01:05:32,887
Do you want my advice?

1390
01:05:32,888 --> 01:05:33,972
I'd be honored.

1391
01:05:35,057 --> 01:05:37,601
Be careful of love stories.

1392
01:05:38,352 --> 01:05:41,145
Think about friendship stories.

1393
01:05:41,146 --> 01:05:44,733
That's where
the really enduring stuff lives.

1394
01:05:45,817 --> 01:05:47,986
- Thank you. I'll remember that.
- HART: Hmm!

1395
01:05:51,156 --> 01:05:52,658
Catch up with you later, George.

1396
01:05:55,160 --> 01:05:56,535
My mother just gave me this.

1397
01:05:56,536 --> 01:05:58,288
I was really touched she gave it to me.

1398
01:05:59,414 --> 01:06:01,540
My well-tempered clavicle.

1399
01:06:01,541 --> 01:06:03,210
Careful. My mother...

1400
01:06:04,002 --> 01:06:05,586
[SOFTLY] Okay. All right...

1401
01:06:05,587 --> 01:06:09,965
Sorry. Now, I know your birthday
isn't until November 19th.

1402
01:06:09,966 --> 01:06:11,050
I'm a scorpion.

1403
01:06:11,051 --> 01:06:13,928
I never doubted that for a second.

1404
01:06:13,929 --> 01:06:16,222
Did you get the sheet music I sent you?

1405
01:06:16,223 --> 01:06:20,393
Ah, I was so busy with exams,
I put them away, honestly, and...

1406
01:06:20,394 --> 01:06:23,938
And then I kind of forgot about them.
But now I've got the time. I promise you.

1407
01:06:23,939 --> 01:06:25,523
I'm going to get a friend of mine

1408
01:06:25,524 --> 01:06:27,400
to play every single one
of those songs for me.

1409
01:06:27,401 --> 01:06:29,193
Take your time.

1410
01:06:29,194 --> 01:06:31,654
That's the wonderful thing
about art, isn't it?

1411
01:06:31,655 --> 01:06:32,864
It waits for you.

1412
01:06:33,865 --> 01:06:36,033
Thank you for all the letters
you wrote me.

1413
01:06:36,034 --> 01:06:37,910
I really enjoyed reading them.

1414
01:06:37,911 --> 01:06:41,038
My roommate couldn't believe I was
actually corresponding with Lorenz Hart.

1415
01:06:41,039 --> 01:06:43,792
I remember in Vermont,
you were drinking red wine.

1416
01:06:44,668 --> 01:06:47,713
Malbec. It's a big Yale drink.

1417
01:06:48,463 --> 01:06:52,007
You ask for the French Malbec,
and then you act

1418
01:06:52,008 --> 01:06:54,260
as if you can actually tell
which vineyard it came from.

1419
01:06:54,261 --> 01:06:55,929
- [BOTH CHUCKLE]
- Oh...

1420
01:06:56,722 --> 01:06:59,390
Don't mention Vermont
around my mother, okay?

1421
01:06:59,391 --> 01:07:01,226
She doesn't know anything
about our little getaway.

1422
01:07:02,394 --> 01:07:04,311
Actually, thank goodness.

1423
01:07:04,312 --> 01:07:07,481
She doesn't know about 90%
of what's going on in my life.

1424
01:07:07,482 --> 01:07:10,151
Well, I feel privileged that I do.

1425
01:07:10,152 --> 01:07:12,446
Or that I did, back in August.

1426
01:07:13,363 --> 01:07:15,865
I've got much more stuff to
report on since then. [LAUGHS]

1427
01:07:15,866 --> 01:07:19,577
Well, tell me about the guys.
That's what I'm interested in.

1428
01:07:19,578 --> 01:07:24,415
[CLICKS TONGUE] Honestly,
I'm much smarter than most of them.

1429
01:07:24,416 --> 01:07:27,877
So I sort of sit back and watch them
trying to impress me.

1430
01:07:27,878 --> 01:07:29,462
It's pretty entertaining.

1431
01:07:29,463 --> 01:07:31,881
If I were a college guy,
I think I would be afraid of you.

1432
01:07:31,882 --> 01:07:35,009
This intelligent, mercilessly observant,

1433
01:07:35,010 --> 01:07:37,636
wickedly unsentimental beauty
sitting there,

1434
01:07:37,637 --> 01:07:40,681
evaluating me from somewhere
behind those green eyes,

1435
01:07:40,682 --> 01:07:42,391
annotating all my gaucheries.

1436
01:07:42,392 --> 01:07:44,351
My God, I would be terrified.

1437
01:07:44,352 --> 01:07:46,271
Hey, I'm not that intimidating.

1438
01:07:47,481 --> 01:07:49,900
Tell me more about this Cooper.

1439
01:07:52,194 --> 01:07:53,319
This is embarrassing. [LAUGHS]

1440
01:07:53,320 --> 01:07:54,612
I love it when you're embarrassed,

1441
01:07:54,613 --> 01:07:57,490
you get this scarlet blush
that washes up over you,

1442
01:07:57,491 --> 01:07:59,701
and a second later it's gone.

1443
01:08:00,202 --> 01:08:02,369
This one might last considerably longer.

1444
01:08:02,370 --> 01:08:04,497
- I'd love to...
- Elizabeth. Hello, Larry.

1445
01:08:04,498 --> 01:08:07,625
I hope I'm not
interrupting anything too weighty.

1446
01:08:07,626 --> 01:08:10,086
Well, weighty affairs will have to wait.

1447
01:08:10,837 --> 01:08:12,379
She's a gem, isn't she?

1448
01:08:12,380 --> 01:08:13,839
Please, Mr. Hammerstein.

1449
01:08:13,840 --> 01:08:15,674
I'll only bother you for a moment.

1450
01:08:15,675 --> 01:08:17,803
Larry, I just wanted to say...

1451
01:08:18,512 --> 01:08:21,597
Well, firstly, I recognize this must be
a difficult night for you.

1452
01:08:21,598 --> 01:08:25,100
No, I'm a professional, Oscar.
We're both professionals,

1453
01:08:25,101 --> 01:08:27,144
we understand the nature of our business.

1454
01:08:27,145 --> 01:08:31,565
Larry, did you really like the show?
I don't think I do the comedy numbers

1455
01:08:31,566 --> 01:08:33,818
half as well as you do.
They're not my strength.

1456
01:08:33,819 --> 01:08:37,822
I laughed my ass off.
I had to have it re-attached.

1457
01:08:37,823 --> 01:08:39,073
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

1458
01:08:39,074 --> 01:08:41,700
Larry, we're the same age,
but you were always the teacher.

1459
01:08:41,701 --> 01:08:44,078
- No, Oscar. I...
- No, your whole career,

1460
01:08:44,079 --> 01:08:45,788
- you showed us the way.
- Well, I doubt...

1461
01:08:45,789 --> 01:08:47,414
You liberated us all.

1462
01:08:47,415 --> 01:08:51,001
You made American songs
finally sound like American speech.

1463
01:08:51,002 --> 01:08:53,712
Stop. I dislike eulogies,
especially my own.

1464
01:08:53,713 --> 01:08:56,007
Oscar, tonight is your night.

1465
01:08:56,633 --> 01:09:00,302
A hit for you and Dick
is a hit for all of us.

1466
01:09:00,303 --> 01:09:03,055
People finally want to go see shows again.

1467
01:09:03,056 --> 01:09:05,975
Real shows. Dick and I
were just tossing around a few ideas.

1468
01:09:05,976 --> 01:09:09,604
- Wonderful.
- Yeah, we have this idea for a big...

1469
01:09:10,689 --> 01:09:12,481
Marco Polo show... huge...

1470
01:09:12,482 --> 01:09:14,191
- Wow.
- ...a kind of musical circus.

1471
01:09:14,192 --> 01:09:16,944
Dick's excited about it.

1472
01:09:16,945 --> 01:09:18,487
He said you're adapting <i>Liliom.</i>

1473
01:09:18,488 --> 01:09:20,281
Well, if we can finagle the rights.

1474
01:09:20,282 --> 01:09:21,366
Sounds exciting.

1475
01:09:21,491 --> 01:09:24,285
- Elizabeth told me she's your protégé.
- Stop.

1476
01:09:24,286 --> 01:09:29,039
"She's the promised kiss of springtime
that makes the lonely winter seem long."

1477
01:09:29,040 --> 01:09:30,124
Oh, please.

1478
01:09:30,125 --> 01:09:33,627
- You wrote a great lyric.
- For a show that didn't run three months.

1479
01:09:33,628 --> 01:09:35,796
- I saw it twice.
- You...

1480
01:09:35,797 --> 01:09:38,215
You know what
we're talking about here, Stevie?

1481
01:09:38,216 --> 01:09:40,634
<i>Very Warm for May.</i>
Produced by Max Gordon.

1482
01:09:40,635 --> 01:09:42,011
Music by Jerome Kern.

1483
01:09:42,012 --> 01:09:44,638
Alvin Theatre. 59 performances.

1484
01:09:44,639 --> 01:09:46,015
[BOTH LAUGH]

1485
01:09:46,016 --> 01:09:50,060
This is my neighbor. He's a kind of
a walking encyclopedia of musical theater.

1486
01:09:50,061 --> 01:09:52,938
Well, I'm a kind of walking pneumonia
for musical theater.

1487
01:09:52,939 --> 01:09:54,982
- Nice to meet you.
- Pleasure to meet you.

1488
01:09:54,983 --> 01:09:56,984
He wants to write musicals
when he grows up.

1489
01:09:56,985 --> 01:09:58,569
Who's your favorite lyricist?

1490
01:09:58,570 --> 01:09:59,738
- Oscar.
- HART: Mmm-hmm.

1491
01:10:00,488 --> 01:10:02,781
Of course.
And what do you think of my work?

1492
01:10:02,782 --> 01:10:04,408
I like it. It's funny.

1493
01:10:04,409 --> 01:10:05,576
Thank you.

1494
01:10:05,577 --> 01:10:06,953
Can be a little sloppy at times.

1495
01:10:07,829 --> 01:10:10,247
OSCAR: He's very tired.
It's been a long day.

1496
01:10:10,248 --> 01:10:13,417
Come on, Stevie.
It's a long ride back to Doylestown.

1497
01:10:13,418 --> 01:10:15,586
- You want to go to the bathroom?
- I'm not tired.

1498
01:10:15,587 --> 01:10:17,671
He asked me what I thought of his work.

1499
01:10:17,672 --> 01:10:19,965
"Weighty affairs will just have to wait"?

1500
01:10:19,966 --> 01:10:22,093
I so regret not having children.

1501
01:10:22,886 --> 01:10:25,220
- Cooper.
- [SIGHS]

1502
01:10:25,221 --> 01:10:27,389
- I can't believe I'm telling you this.
- Tell me.

1503
01:10:27,390 --> 01:10:29,808
You have to remember,
I've had a hopeless crush on this guy

1504
01:10:29,809 --> 01:10:30,935
for over a year.

1505
01:10:30,936 --> 01:10:32,520
Hold this. Come here.

1506
01:10:33,688 --> 01:10:38,151
Renee, may I buy five minutes
of privacy, please?

1507
01:10:39,069 --> 01:10:40,487
{\an8}Anything for you, Larry.

1508
01:10:50,538 --> 01:10:51,665
Thank you.

1509
01:10:53,875 --> 01:10:56,920
Tell me what he looks like,
I'm trying to visualize him.

1510
01:10:57,837 --> 01:11:00,172
Apollo? Blue eyes. Tall.

1511
01:11:00,173 --> 01:11:02,466
So, basically, the skin on his back

1512
01:11:02,467 --> 01:11:04,093
- was flawless...
- [CLICKS TONGUE] Stop.

1513
01:11:04,094 --> 01:11:08,055
It's the night of your birthday.
Tell me everything.

1514
01:11:08,056 --> 01:11:11,810
- A group of my friends are taking...
- Boyfriends, girlfriends?

1515
01:11:12,435 --> 01:11:13,686
- Mixed.
- Okay.

1516
01:11:13,687 --> 01:11:16,063
Come on, Larry, I'm a college lady.

1517
01:11:16,064 --> 01:11:17,356
[CHUCKLES]

1518
01:11:17,357 --> 01:11:21,319
So they're taking me to Mory's,
which is technically no women allowed,

1519
01:11:21,903 --> 01:11:25,489
but they smuggle us up those backstairs
like so much heavily-scented contraband,

1520
01:11:25,490 --> 01:11:30,911
and, of course, one of the girls
has brought along her date.

1521
01:11:30,912 --> 01:11:31,997
Cooper?

1522
01:11:32,580 --> 01:11:36,208
Which is both destroying me
and exhilarating me.

1523
01:11:36,209 --> 01:11:40,005
I mean, he's there. Near me.

1524
01:11:42,048 --> 01:11:43,507
The evening is getting late,

1525
01:11:43,508 --> 01:11:45,593
empty wine bottles
are filling up the table.

1526
01:11:46,594 --> 01:11:48,679
Half of us are underage,

1527
01:11:48,680 --> 01:11:51,682
but we're flirting so shamelessly
with the waiter that nobody seems to care.

1528
01:11:51,683 --> 01:11:54,769
- Drinking your French Malbec.
- Exactly.

1529
01:11:55,478 --> 01:11:57,564
I'm nothing if not a good student.

1530
01:11:58,148 --> 01:12:01,817
That's why everybody loves you, Larry.
You're the best listener I ever met.

1531
01:12:01,818 --> 01:12:05,362
That's because I have absolutely
no interest in myself whatsoever.

1532
01:12:05,363 --> 01:12:07,698
Back to your tale of natal debauchery.

1533
01:12:07,699 --> 01:12:09,784
Empty wine bottles filling the table...

1534
01:12:11,119 --> 01:12:12,454
- So it's late.
- Mmm-hmm.

1535
01:12:12,996 --> 01:12:15,915
- And Marjorie...
- The girl who came with Cooper?

1536
01:12:16,791 --> 01:12:18,500
She's left to go home and study.

1537
01:12:18,501 --> 01:12:19,877
Aww...

1538
01:12:19,878 --> 01:12:22,213
People are staggering out one by one.

1539
01:12:23,048 --> 01:12:24,257
It's midnight.

1540
01:12:25,258 --> 01:12:27,801
And I find myself sitting
right next to him.

1541
01:12:27,802 --> 01:12:29,262
Take your time.

1542
01:12:30,013 --> 01:12:33,640
You know, there's no place else
on earth I'd rather be

1543
01:12:33,641 --> 01:12:36,268
than sitting right here with you.

1544
01:12:36,269 --> 01:12:38,604
Oh, did you get my letter?
There's a party at my place tonight.

1545
01:12:38,605 --> 01:12:40,856
Oh, I think I've got to stay here
and help my mother...

1546
01:12:40,857 --> 01:12:42,274
It's not getting started till late.

1547
01:12:42,275 --> 01:12:45,195
You'll have plenty of time
to work the room here.

1548
01:12:45,904 --> 01:12:49,573
I've got the Golden Gate Quartet
showing up. Promise me you'll come.

1549
01:12:49,574 --> 01:12:51,241
320 Central Park West.

1550
01:12:51,242 --> 01:12:54,620
You said you wanted
to design sets and costumes,

1551
01:12:54,621 --> 01:12:56,914
everybody in New York theater
is gonna be there.

1552
01:12:56,915 --> 01:12:58,249
Okay, back to Cooper.

1553
01:12:59,584 --> 01:13:01,586
- Okay.
- [CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

1554
01:13:02,295 --> 01:13:03,671
We leave Mory's together.

1555
01:13:04,589 --> 01:13:08,134
It's a perfect November night.
A fingernail clipping of a moon.

1556
01:13:09,094 --> 01:13:12,554
He's got his arm around me.
We're both a little drunk,

1557
01:13:12,555 --> 01:13:15,516
stumbling in and out of each other's arms.

1558
01:13:15,517 --> 01:13:18,894
He's wearing this red and green
flannel shirt with the sleeves rolled up.

1559
01:13:18,895 --> 01:13:20,230
Not that you noticed.

1560
01:13:21,189 --> 01:13:22,397
He's looking good!

1561
01:13:22,398 --> 01:13:24,442
- And you?
- Um...

1562
01:13:25,902 --> 01:13:26,945
It's my birthday, right?

1563
01:13:27,737 --> 01:13:30,240
- I'm supposed to be looking good.
- Tasty.

1564
01:13:31,616 --> 01:13:34,660
So I'm leaning
against that flannel work shirt,

1565
01:13:34,661 --> 01:13:36,329
and I'm telling you,

1566
01:13:36,996 --> 01:13:39,623
I can smell the maleness
coming off of him.

1567
01:13:39,624 --> 01:13:40,916
[INHALES DEEPLY]

1568
01:13:40,917 --> 01:13:45,421
I remember thinking that huge purple
letters should have lit up the sky...

1569
01:13:46,923 --> 01:13:48,298
- "Desire."
- Okay.

1570
01:13:48,299 --> 01:13:49,383
Hold on one second.

1571
01:13:49,384 --> 01:13:51,760
I have to go find some ice-water
and pour it down my trousers.

1572
01:13:51,761 --> 01:13:53,513
You may need some extra ice.

1573
01:13:54,222 --> 01:13:57,057
We end up in the basement
of his fraternity,

1574
01:13:57,058 --> 01:14:00,310
in this tawdry sort of derelict bar.

1575
01:14:00,311 --> 01:14:03,397
God only knows how many acts of depravity
have taken place down there.

1576
01:14:03,398 --> 01:14:05,023
And here comes one more.

1577
01:14:05,024 --> 01:14:06,191
Oh, yeah.

1578
01:14:06,192 --> 01:14:08,694
- [BOTH CHUCKLE]
- [ELIZABETH SIGHS]

1579
01:14:08,695 --> 01:14:11,281
So I've been watching this guy for a year,

1580
01:14:12,365 --> 01:14:16,578
dreaming about him, and now, here it is.

1581
01:14:17,453 --> 01:14:19,955
The night of my birthday,

1582
01:14:19,956 --> 01:14:22,791
the only light is coming
from this dim little lamp

1583
01:14:22,792 --> 01:14:25,503
with horses and jockeys
printed on the shade.

1584
01:14:26,212 --> 01:14:28,214
I mean, really, Larry,
what's a girl to do?

1585
01:14:29,048 --> 01:14:30,258
Happy birthday!

1586
01:14:32,969 --> 01:14:34,970
He begins to take off his clothes.

1587
01:14:34,971 --> 01:14:36,139
[HART INHALES DEEPLY]

1588
01:14:37,891 --> 01:14:39,100
[COUGHS]

1589
01:14:41,769 --> 01:14:43,520
You really want to hear this?

1590
01:14:43,521 --> 01:14:45,648
Uh, I'm mildly interested.

1591
01:14:47,817 --> 01:14:48,902
It's humiliating.

1592
01:14:50,361 --> 01:14:51,905
'Cause basically nothing happened.

1593
01:14:53,239 --> 01:14:54,365
Nothing?

1594
01:14:56,242 --> 01:14:58,035
Like you and me at the lake house?

1595
01:14:58,036 --> 01:14:59,120
No.

1596
01:15:00,163 --> 01:15:02,165
That was a deliberate decision
we made, right?

1597
01:15:02,874 --> 01:15:07,045
Based on what? Rationality?
I mean, as rational as you and I ever get.

1598
01:15:08,463 --> 01:15:09,504
[LAUGHS]

1599
01:15:09,505 --> 01:15:10,757
But this...

1600
01:15:12,008 --> 01:15:15,511
[CLICKS TONGUE] This was based on the fact
that he couldn't get the rubber on.

1601
01:15:16,137 --> 01:15:18,013
Oh, no.

1602
01:15:18,014 --> 01:15:19,307
He tried.

1603
01:15:20,225 --> 01:15:21,684
- He tried again.
- No.

1604
01:15:22,602 --> 01:15:25,312
- I tried.
- Oh, stop. [CHUCKLES]

1605
01:15:25,313 --> 01:15:27,314
It was the worst 10 minutes of my life.

1606
01:15:27,315 --> 01:15:29,483
It felt like 10 hours.

1607
01:15:29,484 --> 01:15:30,567
Oh, I'm sorry.

1608
01:15:30,568 --> 01:15:33,196
And you know what the worst part was?

1609
01:15:35,615 --> 01:15:38,076
He just wasn't there, you know?

1610
01:15:39,535 --> 01:15:42,287
He kept mumbling that it was,
um, the wine.

1611
01:15:42,288 --> 01:15:43,414
That, um...

1612
01:15:44,207 --> 01:15:47,668
[SIGHS] ...the rubber was too small,
if you can believe that.

1613
01:15:47,669 --> 01:15:49,002
[CHUCKLES]

1614
01:15:49,003 --> 01:15:51,964
And this whole time what's clear to me

1615
01:15:51,965 --> 01:15:56,844
is that he just... hasn't sufficiently...

1616
01:15:58,471 --> 01:16:01,099
I don't know
what the right word is. Maybe...

1617
01:16:03,017 --> 01:16:06,104
"he-just-doesn't-love-you-enough"
is the right word.

1618
01:16:07,272 --> 01:16:10,108
I mean, there's no way
around that one, is there?

1619
01:16:10,984 --> 01:16:13,903
When the girl loves the guy
with all of her heart,

1620
01:16:14,988 --> 01:16:17,448
and he just doesn't return her feeling?

1621
01:16:18,658 --> 01:16:21,201
Do you have any idea what that feels like?

1622
01:16:21,202 --> 01:16:23,329
"Nobody ever loved me that much."

1623
01:16:24,622 --> 01:16:28,376
I brought into that basement
a year's worth of adoration,

1624
01:16:29,419 --> 01:16:31,421
yeah, studying his photograph,

1625
01:16:32,588 --> 01:16:34,673
memorizing his phone number.

1626
01:16:34,674 --> 01:16:38,511
And there he was, this half-drunk junior

1627
01:16:39,595 --> 01:16:42,848
- who couldn't even pretend to love me...
- [SIGHS]

1628
01:16:42,849 --> 01:16:46,602
And... I wouldn't have minded
if there'd been...

1629
01:16:47,687 --> 01:16:49,938
some... passion underneath.

1630
01:16:49,939 --> 01:16:52,567
- [BOTH LAUGH]
- Or even empathy.

1631
01:16:54,068 --> 01:16:56,821
- [EXHALES DEEPLY]
- There was nothing.

1632
01:16:57,655 --> 01:17:01,409
Just... that lamp with the horses on it.

1633
01:17:02,577 --> 01:17:06,997
[WHISPERS] You deserve so much better.

1634
01:17:06,998 --> 01:17:08,124
Yeah.

1635
01:17:10,126 --> 01:17:12,003
I asked my roommate about it
the next morning,

1636
01:17:12,670 --> 01:17:14,422
you know, girl to girl.

1637
01:17:15,548 --> 01:17:20,303
She said that men sometimes can't
perform because they're too nervous.

1638
01:17:23,389 --> 01:17:26,350
I wish I could believe that to feel
a little bit better about myself.

1639
01:17:26,351 --> 01:17:27,810
But... [CLICKS TONGUE]

1640
01:17:28,311 --> 01:17:31,188
...he was not nervous. Not in the least.

1641
01:17:31,189 --> 01:17:32,356
He had his eyes shut.

1642
01:17:32,357 --> 01:17:35,567
As if he were trying to dream me
into somebody he really wanted.

1643
01:17:35,568 --> 01:17:37,569
[SIGHS] I felt stupid.

1644
01:17:37,570 --> 01:17:39,029
I felt debased.

1645
01:17:39,030 --> 01:17:41,698
I felt furious at myself
that I could allow him

1646
01:17:41,699 --> 01:17:44,660
to make me feel so worthless. [SIGHS]

1647
01:17:45,995 --> 01:17:48,205
[LAUGHING] We tried
a few creative alternatives.

1648
01:17:48,206 --> 01:17:49,832
Oh, no. [LAUGHS]

1649
01:17:51,167 --> 01:17:53,753
It got uglier and uglier.

1650
01:17:54,462 --> 01:17:58,633
Finally, he said,
"Elizabeth, I owe you a rain check."

1651
01:18:00,593 --> 01:18:01,928
And that...

1652
01:18:02,553 --> 01:18:04,722
That was my 20th birthday.

1653
01:18:06,099 --> 01:18:07,307
Ta-da.

1654
01:18:07,308 --> 01:18:08,476
Jesus wept.

1655
01:18:11,312 --> 01:18:12,521
But it gets worse.

1656
01:18:12,522 --> 01:18:13,730
I don't think I can take it.

1657
01:18:13,731 --> 01:18:15,148
Okay, I can take it.

1658
01:18:15,149 --> 01:18:19,444
But just tell me in a way that doesn't
make me ashamed to be a human being.

1659
01:18:19,445 --> 01:18:20,530
[SIGHS]

1660
01:18:21,656 --> 01:18:22,740
That's going to be difficult.

1661
01:18:24,200 --> 01:18:26,576
About a week later... [SIGHS]

1662
01:18:26,577 --> 01:18:28,538
...everybody's leaving for Thanksgiving.

1663
01:18:29,831 --> 01:18:32,583
He gives me a call.
Would I like to have dinner with him?

1664
01:18:33,376 --> 01:18:36,128
- You know me. No pride.
- [CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

1665
01:18:36,129 --> 01:18:40,007
I say, "Sure," and make my way over
to his fraternity again,

1666
01:18:41,175 --> 01:18:43,928
which sits under this huge gingko tree.

1667
01:18:44,679 --> 01:18:46,888
The leaves have turned yellow,

1668
01:18:46,889 --> 01:18:49,642
the trunk of the tree
is black from the rain.

1669
01:18:50,351 --> 01:18:53,354
I'm thinking this is the most
beautiful thing I've ever seen.

1670
01:18:54,272 --> 01:18:55,940
I remember saying to myself,

1671
01:18:56,774 --> 01:18:58,860
[WHISPERS] "God is giving you
a second chance."

1672
01:18:59,819 --> 01:19:00,986
We go up to his room,

1673
01:19:00,987 --> 01:19:03,448
his roommate has already left
for the holiday.

1674
01:19:04,240 --> 01:19:05,658
The door clicks shut,

1675
01:19:06,826 --> 01:19:07,827
and suddenly...

1676
01:19:09,245 --> 01:19:11,955
there's no more discussion about dinner.

1677
01:19:11,956 --> 01:19:13,915
Rain check cashed!

1678
01:19:13,916 --> 01:19:15,292
In spades.

1679
01:19:15,293 --> 01:19:17,085
I mean, it's suddenly pouring.

1680
01:19:17,086 --> 01:19:19,421
We're practically
tearing each other's clothes off.

1681
01:19:19,422 --> 01:19:21,174
There is no conversation.

1682
01:19:22,049 --> 01:19:23,301
And this time...

1683
01:19:24,719 --> 01:19:26,262
there is no difficulty.

1684
01:19:27,388 --> 01:19:30,724
Not the first time.
Not the second time.

1685
01:19:30,725 --> 01:19:32,310
Stop it.

1686
01:19:34,187 --> 01:19:38,190
He says to me,
"Happy belated birthday, Elizabeth."

1687
01:19:38,191 --> 01:19:39,275
Mmm.

1688
01:19:40,943 --> 01:19:44,906
And you want to hear the unbelievable
ending to this sordid little story?

1689
01:19:46,699 --> 01:19:48,409
That was the last time I saw him.

1690
01:19:50,495 --> 01:19:53,789
That was November. Over four months ago.

1691
01:19:55,249 --> 01:19:59,461
I was absolutely sure he'd call.
If only to have sex again, right?

1692
01:19:59,462 --> 01:20:01,714
No. Never.

1693
01:20:02,548 --> 01:20:04,341
I thought he'd write.

1694
01:20:04,342 --> 01:20:05,551
No.

1695
01:20:06,302 --> 01:20:07,928
So I call him, of course.
[SCOFFS]

1696
01:20:07,929 --> 01:20:09,179
HART: Mmm.

1697
01:20:09,180 --> 01:20:11,097
He couldn't get off the phone fast enough.

1698
01:20:11,098 --> 01:20:12,475
[SIGHS]

1699
01:20:12,642 --> 01:20:14,060
So I wrote to him.

1700
01:20:15,645 --> 01:20:18,230
- A four-page typed letter. Single-spaced.
- Oh, no.

1701
01:20:18,231 --> 01:20:19,649
No response.

1702
01:20:20,274 --> 01:20:24,320
I tell myself it was like a fever dream,
you know?

1703
01:20:25,279 --> 01:20:27,490
And maybe the fever finally broke.

1704
01:20:28,616 --> 01:20:31,619
And it all sounds sane and sensible.

1705
01:20:34,038 --> 01:20:35,456
But you know something?

1706
01:20:36,916 --> 01:20:40,503
If he called me right now,
right this very second,

1707
01:20:41,921 --> 01:20:43,965
I'd drop everything in my life and...

1708
01:20:45,091 --> 01:20:49,386
drive three hours, drive 30 hours
just to spend one more night with him.

1709
01:20:49,387 --> 01:20:51,429
What is the matter with me, Larry?

1710
01:20:51,430 --> 01:20:55,351
Why would you drive 30 hours to see
someone who treated you like that?

1711
01:20:58,271 --> 01:20:59,981
Because I'm in love with him?

1712
01:21:01,148 --> 01:21:02,149
You are?

1713
01:21:03,109 --> 01:21:06,696
It's illogical. Obsessional. Pathetic.

1714
01:21:07,697 --> 01:21:09,824
And this is not the first time
this has happened to me.

1715
01:21:11,117 --> 01:21:12,618
It keeps happening to me.

1716
01:21:14,412 --> 01:21:16,872
I feel like I can't see people clearly.

1717
01:21:18,165 --> 01:21:21,084
I wrote a song once, years ago,

1718
01:21:21,085 --> 01:21:23,253
called <i>The Heart is Quicker
Than the Eye.</i>

1719
01:21:23,254 --> 01:21:25,672
It's not a great song,
but it's a good title.

1720
01:21:25,673 --> 01:21:27,842
And it's true, I think.

1721
01:21:28,676 --> 01:21:34,514
The head has nothing to do
with the madness of love.

1722
01:21:34,515 --> 01:21:36,642
[CHUCKLES] And...

1723
01:21:37,184 --> 01:21:40,562
It doesn't matter at all
about worthiness, does it?

1724
01:21:40,563 --> 01:21:44,190
We invest our hearts in worthless stocks.

1725
01:21:44,191 --> 01:21:46,443
And we know they're worthless.

1726
01:21:46,444 --> 01:21:50,656
But we cling to them like little children
clutching their little stuffed bears.

1727
01:21:51,741 --> 01:21:54,785
[SIGHING] Oh, Elizabeth.

1728
01:21:56,829 --> 01:21:58,080
Tell me truthfully.

1729
01:22:00,124 --> 01:22:01,626
How do you feel about me?

1730
01:22:04,962 --> 01:22:06,047
How do you mean?

1731
01:22:07,214 --> 01:22:08,215
I mean,

1732
01:22:09,216 --> 01:22:12,470
at the lake house,
with the light burning off the water,

1733
01:22:14,096 --> 01:22:16,098
we talked through half the night,

1734
01:22:17,266 --> 01:22:19,060
and I touched your shoulder...

1735
01:22:19,852 --> 01:22:22,480
Did you actually love me
a little bit that night?

1736
01:22:23,773 --> 01:22:25,358
You know I love you, Larry.

1737
01:22:27,985 --> 01:22:29,195
You do?

1738
01:22:32,531 --> 01:22:35,826
Just... not that way.

1739
01:22:43,834 --> 01:22:48,005
You said you'd drive 30 hours
to see Cooper.

1740
01:22:49,340 --> 01:22:51,801
How many hours would you drive to see me?

1741
01:22:52,635 --> 01:22:55,345
Oh. [LAUGHS] My hands are shaking.

1742
01:22:55,346 --> 01:22:56,888
[HART MUMBLES]

1743
01:22:56,889 --> 01:22:59,474
I feel something wiser
and deeper for you.

1744
01:22:59,475 --> 01:23:01,893
- Mmm. Thank you.
- Respect.

1745
01:23:01,894 --> 01:23:05,939
Gratitude for the generosity
and selflessness you've shown me.

1746
01:23:05,940 --> 01:23:08,942
No one has ever been more interested
in my life than you have.

1747
01:23:08,943 --> 01:23:12,612
I don't deserve a friendship like yours.
I am so grateful for you.

1748
01:23:12,613 --> 01:23:14,781
I will be grateful forever.

1749
01:23:14,782 --> 01:23:17,534
I'm grateful to you, too,
for resurrecting me.

1750
01:23:17,535 --> 01:23:19,160
- [KNOCK ON DOOR]
- Stop.

1751
01:23:19,161 --> 01:23:20,537
RENEE: Larry! There's people out here.

1752
01:23:20,538 --> 01:23:22,081
[SPUTTERS] One second!

1753
01:23:27,086 --> 01:23:29,046
- Can I ask you something?
- [CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

1754
01:23:30,214 --> 01:23:32,674
Something that's probably
too personal for me to ask?

1755
01:23:32,675 --> 01:23:36,137
Too personal is the only thing
that I'm interested in.

1756
01:23:36,804 --> 01:23:39,640
Uh... My mother...

1757
01:23:40,349 --> 01:23:43,393
You know, she works for the Guild,
she knows everybody.

1758
01:23:43,394 --> 01:23:46,271
So she saw us spending time together
last summer...

1759
01:23:46,272 --> 01:23:48,232
I see where this is headed.

1760
01:23:49,483 --> 01:23:52,736
She said to me... I don't...
I don't know how to say this.

1761
01:23:52,737 --> 01:23:53,821
Just say it.

1762
01:23:56,115 --> 01:23:57,116
Okay.

1763
01:23:58,576 --> 01:24:00,535
She said to me, more than once,

1764
01:24:00,536 --> 01:24:03,414
"Elizabeth, not only is he twice your age,

1765
01:24:04,498 --> 01:24:08,418
"but I don't think
his primary interest is women."

1766
01:24:08,419 --> 01:24:09,628
What did you say?

1767
01:24:10,755 --> 01:24:13,214
I said, "Look, Mother, I know what I know.

1768
01:24:13,215 --> 01:24:14,841
"And I know what we're both feeling."

1769
01:24:14,842 --> 01:24:17,094
Mmm-hmm. What are we both feeling?

1770
01:24:21,390 --> 01:24:23,100
"Irrational adoration?"

1771
01:24:25,186 --> 01:24:30,357
And what may I ask does your mother
think she knows of my primary interest?

1772
01:24:31,525 --> 01:24:34,278
I'm sorry. I shouldn't have said anything.

1773
01:24:35,112 --> 01:24:36,280
Please forgive me.

1774
01:24:37,740 --> 01:24:42,453
To all our mothers.
May they remain mercifully silent.

1775
01:24:43,704 --> 01:24:45,914
I apologize.
That was stupid of me to have asked.

1776
01:24:45,915 --> 01:24:48,000
And I do know what I know,
and what I feel.

1777
01:24:48,793 --> 01:24:50,960
Here's what you tell that mother of yours,

1778
01:24:50,961 --> 01:24:52,504
as she sits by the fire,

1779
01:24:52,505 --> 01:24:55,507
wistfully counting up her royalties
from <i>Oklahoma!</i>

1780
01:24:55,508 --> 01:24:59,261
You tell her that Larry Hart
is drunk with beauty.

1781
01:25:00,346 --> 01:25:02,431
And italicize the word "drunk."

1782
01:25:02,932 --> 01:25:05,642
Drunk with beauty, wherever he finds it.

1783
01:25:05,643 --> 01:25:10,271
In men, in women,
in the smell of cigar stores,

1784
01:25:10,272 --> 01:25:15,151
in the impossible beauty
of a 20-year-old poet

1785
01:25:15,152 --> 01:25:19,990
with pale green eyes and two tiny freckles
on her left cheek.

1786
01:25:24,787 --> 01:25:25,871
Are you all right?

1787
01:25:26,914 --> 01:25:29,415
It's... [INHALES DEEPLY]

1788
01:25:29,416 --> 01:25:31,417
- ...my cigarette heart.
- [DOOR OPENS]

1789
01:25:31,418 --> 01:25:33,795
Larry, Dick Rodgers
is looking for his coat.

1790
01:25:33,796 --> 01:25:35,047
HART: Coming.

1791
01:25:51,981 --> 01:25:53,189
Introduce me?

1792
01:25:53,190 --> 01:25:56,317
[GRUNTING] Thank you, Renee.

1793
01:25:56,318 --> 01:25:58,529
Wonderful, thank you so much.

1794
01:25:59,196 --> 01:26:03,492
Dick, I want to introduce you
to my protégé, Elizabeth Weiland.

1795
01:26:04,910 --> 01:26:06,078
Your protégé?

1796
01:26:06,954 --> 01:26:08,329
- Hello.
- Hello.

1797
01:26:08,330 --> 01:26:10,790
Well, you've got yourself
a damn good role model there

1798
01:26:10,791 --> 01:26:13,251
if you can stay away from the bourbon.

1799
01:26:13,252 --> 01:26:18,047
Mmm. She's interested in writing
and set design and costumes.

1800
01:26:18,048 --> 01:26:19,466
Okay, really?

1801
01:26:19,592 --> 01:26:21,760
Mr. Rodgers, the show tonight,

1802
01:26:22,469 --> 01:26:24,053
I thought it was magnificent.

1803
01:26:24,054 --> 01:26:25,221
Well, thank you.

1804
01:26:25,222 --> 01:26:27,473
It was as perfect a musical show
as I've ever seen.

1805
01:26:27,474 --> 01:26:29,893
Well, that's a lovely compliment.

1806
01:26:29,894 --> 01:26:32,020
Your mother's with the Guild, am I right?

1807
01:26:32,021 --> 01:26:34,439
- Yes, Theresa Weiland.
- Yeah, Theresa, yeah.

1808
01:26:34,440 --> 01:26:37,233
- Right, so you've seen a lot of shows.
- Too many shows.

1809
01:26:37,234 --> 01:26:39,152
[ALL LAUGHING]

1810
01:26:39,153 --> 01:26:40,236
Yeah.

1811
01:26:40,237 --> 01:26:41,322
I know what you mean.

1812
01:26:41,906 --> 01:26:44,616
But tonight what I saw was what
I'd always hoped a show might be.

1813
01:26:44,617 --> 01:26:47,453
Uplifting. Smart. Magical.

1814
01:26:47,578 --> 01:26:50,997
Larry, this is the most perceptive young
woman you've ever introduced me to.

1815
01:26:50,998 --> 01:26:52,457
[HART CHUCKLES]

1816
01:26:52,458 --> 01:26:54,043
- I've had a good teacher.
- HART: Mmm-hmm.

1817
01:26:54,835 --> 01:26:56,502
So, what do you write?

1818
01:26:56,503 --> 01:26:58,422
At this point, poetry mostly.

1819
01:26:58,881 --> 01:27:00,757
It's very strong.

1820
01:27:00,758 --> 01:27:02,550
And you do set design, too?

1821
01:27:02,551 --> 01:27:04,010
- I'm studying.
- RODGERS: Right.

1822
01:27:04,011 --> 01:27:07,972
Well, I'd love to...
read some of your poems.

1823
01:27:07,973 --> 01:27:13,145
Uh... See your sketches. This is my...
This is my private number.

1824
01:27:14,647 --> 01:27:15,731
I'm flattered.

1825
01:27:16,440 --> 01:27:19,943
I haven't seen Dorothy around.
Is... Is... Is your wife here?

1826
01:27:19,944 --> 01:27:22,320
No, she's headed back to the apartment.
We're all going to meet up there

1827
01:27:22,321 --> 01:27:24,280
to look at the late reviews, Larry.

1828
01:27:24,281 --> 01:27:27,784
Yeah, so I'd love for you
to join us, Elizabeth.

1829
01:27:27,785 --> 01:27:30,703
It would be refreshing to have someone
of the younger generation amongst us.

1830
01:27:30,704 --> 01:27:32,789
And maybe you can
explain to me, Elizabeth,

1831
01:27:32,790 --> 01:27:35,334
why exactly the young girls
scream over Sinatra.

1832
01:27:35,960 --> 01:27:37,752
I don't scream over Sinatra.

1833
01:27:37,753 --> 01:27:39,879
No, she screams under Sinatra.

1834
01:27:39,880 --> 01:27:41,673
Okay, Larry!

1835
01:27:41,674 --> 01:27:43,216
[ALL LAUGHING]

1836
01:27:43,217 --> 01:27:45,426
Larry, of course, you're welcome to come.

1837
01:27:45,427 --> 01:27:49,180
Oh, I'm going to try to make it, I'm just
throwing a little soirée over at my place.

1838
01:27:49,181 --> 01:27:50,640
I've got the Golden Gate Quartet coming...

1839
01:27:50,641 --> 01:27:54,519
Well, I can't compete with Larry
in the soirée department.

1840
01:27:54,520 --> 01:27:56,688
- I'd love to stop over.
- You would?

1841
01:27:56,689 --> 01:27:58,314
MAN: Dick, you coming?

1842
01:27:58,315 --> 01:27:59,774
Yep, yep.

1843
01:27:59,775 --> 01:28:01,067
Do you have a ride?

1844
01:28:01,068 --> 01:28:02,777
You know what,
I can take her in a cab later.

1845
01:28:02,778 --> 01:28:04,487
We're going right now
if you want to come with us?

1846
01:28:04,488 --> 01:28:06,198
- I'd love to.
- RODGERS: Great.

1847
01:28:06,991 --> 01:28:09,367
Just let me inform my mom.

1848
01:28:09,368 --> 01:28:11,244
The dutiful daughter.

1849
01:28:11,245 --> 01:28:12,246
[RODGERS CHUCKLES]

1850
01:28:14,039 --> 01:28:17,418
RODGERS: Wow. She is...
She is so lovely, right?

1851
01:28:18,585 --> 01:28:20,461
She's really striking.

1852
01:28:20,462 --> 01:28:22,839
Are you... Are you and she...

1853
01:28:22,840 --> 01:28:26,760
Oh, no, no. I mean, I'm in love with her,

1854
01:28:27,428 --> 01:28:30,347
but, uh, everybody's in love with her.

1855
01:28:31,557 --> 01:28:33,349
Just not that way.

1856
01:28:33,350 --> 01:28:34,435
Okay.

1857
01:28:38,522 --> 01:28:39,648
HART: Hmm.

1858
01:28:41,734 --> 01:28:42,735
[HART SIGHS SOFTLY]

1859
01:28:44,028 --> 01:28:45,570
So we'll see you later on tonight?

1860
01:28:45,571 --> 01:28:46,905
Absolutely.

1861
01:28:48,907 --> 01:28:50,492
[CHUCKLES] Mmm-hmm.

1862
01:28:51,493 --> 01:28:52,661
Hmm.

1863
01:28:53,871 --> 01:28:55,247
Thank you for everything.

1864
01:28:56,957 --> 01:28:58,583
Mr. Rodgers.

1865
01:28:58,584 --> 01:28:59,918
Miss Weiland.

1866
01:29:02,004 --> 01:29:03,047
Thank you.

1867
01:29:03,839 --> 01:29:05,299
And we'll see you later, Larry, right?

1868
01:29:08,927 --> 01:29:12,890
"With a song in my heart,
I behold your adorable face!"

1869
01:29:25,235 --> 01:29:27,696
[INHALES DEEPLY]

1870
01:29:35,245 --> 01:29:38,581
You ever meet someone,
and you know instantly

1871
01:29:38,582 --> 01:29:42,877
that both your lives
are going to be irretrievably altered?

1872
01:29:42,878 --> 01:29:46,923
Just as I suspected.
You are a sentimentalist.

1873
01:29:46,924 --> 01:29:48,841
[HART LAUGHS]

1874
01:29:48,842 --> 01:29:50,134
When do you get off work?

1875
01:29:50,135 --> 01:29:51,761
I got to lock this joint up.

1876
01:29:51,762 --> 01:29:54,680
Ah, what about you, Knuckles,
you're done here, right?

1877
01:29:54,681 --> 01:29:56,140
Not yet.

1878
01:29:56,141 --> 01:29:59,770
Oh, 'cause I am throwing an enormous party
at my place tonight.

1879
01:30:00,854 --> 01:30:02,022
[SIGHS]

1880
01:30:02,898 --> 01:30:04,733
I forgot to give her the presents.

1881
01:30:06,151 --> 01:30:07,860
[SIGHS]

1882
01:30:07,861 --> 01:30:10,113
I'm having such trouble
with sleeves recently.

1883
01:30:10,114 --> 01:30:12,407
I have arthritis in this shoulder.

1884
01:30:13,367 --> 01:30:15,244
I'm going to have to start
wearing a cloak.

1885
01:30:15,869 --> 01:30:19,832
I mean it. Single-handedly,
I'm going to bring back the cloak.

1886
01:30:21,166 --> 01:30:22,209
[HART SIGHS]

1887
01:30:23,544 --> 01:30:24,669
[CLICKS TONGUE]

1888
01:30:24,670 --> 01:30:30,174
You're going to see me
on opening nights with a top hat

1889
01:30:30,175 --> 01:30:35,139
and a cloak, flitting through the fog
with a silver-tipped cane.

1890
01:30:35,931 --> 01:30:38,057
You boys are coming tonight, right?

1891
01:30:38,058 --> 01:30:41,228
She's going to be there.
I'm telling you, she will.

1892
01:30:41,854 --> 01:30:43,229
She'll arrive late.

1893
01:30:43,230 --> 01:30:47,483
And get this,
'cause this is the remarkable part,

1894
01:30:47,484 --> 01:30:51,070
sometime late, maybe around 5:00 a.m.,

1895
01:30:51,071 --> 01:30:53,489
after a little too much Malbec,

1896
01:30:53,490 --> 01:30:56,659
she's going to turn to me and say,

1897
01:30:56,660 --> 01:30:59,871
"Hey, Larry, what are you reading?

1898
01:30:59,872 --> 01:31:02,290
"Hey, Larry, when's your birthday?"

1899
01:31:02,291 --> 01:31:05,001
For the first time in her life,

1900
01:31:05,002 --> 01:31:08,964
she's going to be interested in me.

1901
01:31:09,798 --> 01:31:12,049
It has to happen sometime, right?

1902
01:31:12,050 --> 01:31:14,385
All the other guys have disappointed her.

1903
01:31:14,386 --> 01:31:17,514
But I never will. I'm just...

1904
01:31:18,557 --> 01:31:20,976
a little touch of Larry in the night.

1905
01:31:22,561 --> 01:31:25,104
Knuckles. Some travelin' music.

1906
01:31:25,105 --> 01:31:27,149
[PLAYING PIANO]

1907
01:31:29,568 --> 01:31:30,569
MORTY: [SINGING] <i>Blue moon</i>

1908
01:31:32,863 --> 01:31:36,200
<i>You saw me standing alone</i>

1909
01:31:36,825 --> 01:31:37,825
Wise guy.

1910
01:31:37,826 --> 01:31:41,205
<i>Without a dream in my heart</i>

1911
01:31:42,873 --> 01:31:45,918
<i>Without a love of my own</i>

1912
01:31:47,211 --> 01:31:51,381
Well, it's a helluva lot better than
<i>The Surrey With the Fucking Fringe On Top.</i>

1913
01:31:52,174 --> 01:31:55,260
Larry, you coming uptown
to Dick's with us?

1914
01:31:55,427 --> 01:31:57,971
Oh, no, you go on ahead,
I'll be up there later.

1915
01:31:59,014 --> 01:32:03,476
MORTY AND RENEE: [SINGING]
<i>You knew just what I was there for</i>

1916
01:32:03,477 --> 01:32:07,355
{\an8}<i>You heard me saying a prayer for</i>

1917
01:32:07,356 --> 01:32:08,689
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

1918
01:32:08,690 --> 01:32:12,026
<i>Someone I really could care for</i>

1919
01:32:12,027 --> 01:32:16,447
That's not bad. Triple feminine rhymes,
and they all make sense.

1920
01:32:16,448 --> 01:32:19,284
MORTY: [SINGING]
<i>And then suddenly you appeared before me</i>

1921
01:32:20,410 --> 01:32:23,997
MORTY AND RENEE: [SINGING]
<i>The only one my arms will ever hold</i>

1922
01:32:25,082 --> 01:32:27,458
<i>And I heard somebody whisper</i>

1923
01:32:27,459 --> 01:32:29,669
<i>Please adore me</i>

1924
01:32:29,670 --> 01:32:34,757
<i>And when I looked
The moon had turned to gold</i>

1925
01:32:34,758 --> 01:32:36,426
<i>Blue moon</i>

1926
01:32:43,809 --> 01:32:48,563
Larry, I think this is the beginning
of a beautiful friendship.

1927
01:32:49,147 --> 01:32:50,565
"Isn't it romantic?"

1928
01:32:51,441 --> 01:32:52,609
Not really, no.

1929
01:32:56,655 --> 01:32:59,991
You know, it wasn't even supposed to
be called <i>Blue Moon.</i>

1930
01:32:59,992 --> 01:33:03,452
I called it <i>The Bad in Every Man.</i>

1931
01:33:03,453 --> 01:33:06,330
We wrote it for this movie,
<i>Manhattan Melodrama.</i>

1932
01:33:06,331 --> 01:33:10,334
Jack Robbins, formerly "Rabinowitz,"
he had his name circumcised over at MGM,

1933
01:33:10,335 --> 01:33:12,336
he hears the song,
he calls us into his office,

1934
01:33:12,337 --> 01:33:14,005
he lowers his pastrami, says...

1935
01:33:14,006 --> 01:33:17,091
[IN NASAL VOICE]
"Dick, I love the melody.

1936
01:33:17,092 --> 01:33:19,552
"Strong as anything you've ever written.

1937
01:33:19,553 --> 01:33:24,015
"But, Larry, those words,
they're too artsy-fartsy!

1938
01:33:24,016 --> 01:33:27,518
"They're not too artsy-fartsy for me.
I know how brilliant you guys are.

1939
01:33:27,519 --> 01:33:30,062
"But you have to write
for the schmucks in the dark.

1940
01:33:30,063 --> 01:33:31,647
"Nobody's going to sing that lyric."

1941
01:33:31,648 --> 01:33:33,399
[IN NORMAL VOICE] So I said,
"What's wrong with it?"

1942
01:33:33,400 --> 01:33:36,319
He said... [IN NASAL VOICE] "I can't even
remember the fucking title!

1943
01:33:36,320 --> 01:33:39,238
"Boys, give me
something I can promote."

1944
01:33:39,239 --> 01:33:41,657
[IN NORMAL VOICE] So I say,
"What do you want me to call it?"

1945
01:33:41,658 --> 01:33:42,742
<i>Blue Moon?</i>

1946
01:33:42,743 --> 01:33:45,787
Punchline, biggest hit we ever wrote.

1947
01:33:46,538 --> 01:33:48,540
[SOULFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

1948
01:34:03,972 --> 01:34:05,974
[<i>THIS FUNNY WORLD</i> PLAYING]

1949
01:36:27,574 --> 01:36:29,576
[MELLOW MUSIC PLAYING]

